<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Fourth son of Finarfin and Eärwen, and younger brother of Finrod Felagund, Angrod, and Galadriel. In Beleriand, he and his brother Angrod held the highlands of Dorthonion as vassals of their elder brother Finrod. A prince of the House of Finarfin, he belonged to one of the chief Noldorin lines active in the wars and realms of the First Age.Immortal angelic spirits created by Eru Ilúvatar before the beginning of the World, whose being originated in the Timeless Halls beyond creation. Through the Music of the Ainur, they participated in the vision and shaping of Arda. Those who chose to enter the physical world to complete its material development became known as the Powers of Arda, divided into the mightier Valar and the lesser Maiar. As beings of free will, they could rebel against their creator, as demonstrated by Melkor's fall into darkness.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia associated with the Valië Yavanna, the Queen of Earth, possessing a strong affinity for animals and growing things. Chosen by Yavanna, he was later sent to Middle-earth as one of the Istari in the Third Age. His name in the original tongue relates to his connection with nature, and in later ages he became known for his love of beasts and birds above the concerns of Elves and Men.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia of Oromë the Huntsman, chosen by his lord to be sent to Middle-earth as one of the Istari. He took his friend Pallando with him on this mission, and the two were known collectively as the Blue Wizards or Ithryn Luin. Their work was associated with the far East and South of Middle-earth. In some accounts Alatar is also called Morinehtar, meaning Darkness-slayer.A swan-haven of the Falmari on the shores of Aman beside Belegaer, lying between the Calacirya and Araman in northern Eldamar. Built around a natural harbor of rock with a carved entrance, the city was both walled and shaped by the sea. Its quays and mansions were adorned with pearls and mother of pearl from the waters and with jewels received from the Noldor, and it was lit by many lamps so that the haven shone over the sea. The famed swanships of the Teleri were moored there, and the harbor itself was an emblem of their sea craft and love of the waves.The western continent of Arda beyond Belegaer, also called the Blessed Realm and the Undying Lands. It contains Valinor, the dwelling place of the Valar, and Eldamar, the Elvish lands of the Amanyar along the coast. The Pelóri mountains were raised along the eastern shore as a defense against Melkor, with Taniquetil as the highest peak, and the Calacirya cleft let the light of Valinor reach Eldamar and Tol Eressëa. Beyond the mountains lay regions such as Araman and Avathar. In the far north, the Helcaraxë once joined the West to Middle-earth by grinding ice, before that bridge was removed and the way to the West was guarded by the seas.Those of Aman, a term used by the Noldorin Exiles to describe themselves and those Elves who dwelt in the Blessed Realm of Valinor. The distinction arose after the Flight of the Noldor, when terminology shifted from the older Calaquendi/Moriquendi classification to the more geographically-based Amanyar/Úmanyar division, which proved less offensive to the Sindar who had never seen the Light of the Two Trees.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>The younger of the twin sons of Fëanor and Nerdanel, and the youngest of their seven children born in Valinor during the days of the Two Trees. Red-haired like his twin brother Amrod, he was alike with him in mood and face, though twins were very rare among the Eldar. He and Amrod were known as hunters and are usually remembered together among the sons of Fëanor.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>The elder of the twin sons of Fëanor and Nerdanel, and the sixth of their seven children. Red-haired, though his hair grew darker than that of his twin Amras, he was alike with his brother in mood and face, and twins were very rare among the Eldar. He and Amras were known as hunters and are among the least separately described of the princes of the Noldor.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Vanyar">Vanyar</a><br><br>A Vanyarin Elf beloved by Finrod Felagund. Though they loved one another, they did not wed, and when Finrod joined the Exile of the Noldor, Amárië did not follow him to Beleriand. According to some accounts, she was not permitted to accompany him. She remained in Valinor, linking her story to the separation between the Vanyar of Aman and the Noldorin exiles.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Wife of Fingolfin and mother of four children: Fingon, Turgon, Aredhel, and Argon. She was a Noldo whose name means Holiest in Quenya. Little is told of her, except that she did not leave Aman, largely because of her close friendship with Eärwen, wife of Finarfin.The sword Narsil reforged in Rivendell in T.A. 3018 for Aragorn, the heir of Isildur. Its blade bore designs of Seven Stars between the rayed Sun and crescent Moon, symbols associated with Elendil and his sons Anárion and Isildur, together with many cirth. In daylight it shone red, and in moonlight it shone cold. Aragorn bore it as the Sword That Was Broken and the Sword Reforged, a sign of his lineage and claim, and Galadriel later gave it a sheath worked with silver, gold, runes, and gems. The Quenya name means Flame of the West.Melkor's great fortress in the Iron Mountains, a dark stronghold beneath Thangorodrim that became the seat of his power in the First Age. It began as an outlying fortress and armoury to Utumno, but after Utumno was destroyed and Melkor returned to Middle-earth he rebuilt it and raised the towers of Thangorodrim above its gates. The citadel was primarily underground, with deep chambers and vaults hidden beneath the earth, while its visible peaks of ash and slag dominated the northern sky. The Noldor besieged it for centuries until the siege was broken at the Dagor Bragollach, and it was finally destroyed in the War of Wrath at the end of the First Age.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Third son of Finarfin and Eärwen, brother to Finrod Felagund, Aegnor, and Galadriel, and father of Orodreth. In Beleriand, he and his younger brother Aegnor ruled over Dorthonion as vassals of their elder brother Finrod, holding the highlands during the Siege of Angband. He belonged to the House of Finarfin and to the Noldorin leadership of the northern marches.The Exalted or High Ones of Arda, comprising the eight greatest among the Valar: Manwë, Varda, Ulmo, Yavanna, Aulë, Mandos, Nienna, and Oromë. These mightiest of the Powers possessed supreme authority and influence over the shaping and governance of Arda, standing above their peers in majesty and power.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>The White Lady of the Noldor, also called Ar-Feiniel, third child and only daughter of Fingolfin and Anairë. Her brothers were Fingon, Turgon, and Argon. Tall and strong, she was fond of hunting and riding in the forests, with pale skin, dark hair, and garments of silver and white. She dwelt in Gondolin with her brother Turgon but longed for wider lands, and her story is closely tied to Nan Elmoth, Eöl the Dark Elf, and her son Maeglin.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Argon was the fourth and last child of Fingolfin and Anairë, and the youngest son of Fingolfin. His elder brothers were Fingon and Turgon, and his sister was Aredhel. His Quenya name was Arakáno, meaning High Commander, a name connected with his impetuous character.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia associated with fire and with the Sun. In the days of the Two Trees, she served in the gardens of Vána, tending the golden flowers and watering them with dew gathered from Laurelin. Melkor failed to corrupt her, and the Valar chose her to guide the vessel of the Sun through the airs of Arda. Her Quenya name means Maiden of Sun.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin Elf, one of Angrod's people, who later dwelt among the followers of Círdan the Shipwright. He travelled with his companion Gelmir as a messenger of Círdan, and the two encountered Tuor near Annon-in-Gelydh, the Gate of the Noldor. Their eyes marked them as Calaquendi born in Valinor before the Exile. Arminas is a Sindarin name meaning Royal Tower.The Secondborn, the race of mortal Men who awoke in Middle-earth when the Sun first rose in the heavens late in the First Age, millennia after the awakening of the Elves. Unlike the immortal Firstborn, they were granted the gift of mortality and freedom from the circles of the world, though this gift was often perceived as a doom by those who did not understand Eru's design.A sweet-smelling herb also known as kingsfoil or asëa aranion, valued for healing wounds, poison, and evil influences such as the Black Breath. It held special power in the hands of the Kings of Gondor. Athelas grew notably on Númenor and was brought to Middle-earth by the Númenóreans, later appearing sparsely in the North where the Men of Westernesse had camped or lived. By the end of the Third Age its virtues were remembered especially by the Rangers of the North, while in Gondor it was valued mostly for its scent and its place in old verses.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>One of the Aratar, the smith and master of crafts among the Valar, and third most powerful among them. He governs the substances of the earth and delights in works of craft, from small works to the forging of lands, mountains, rocks, gems, and minerals. Husband to Yavanna, he dwells with her in central Valinor. The Dwarves call him Mahal, the Maker, and the Noldor became his students and friends in Valinor; among the Maiar associated with him were Curumo and Mairon.The Refusers or Unwilling, those Quendi who rejected the summons of the Valar and refused to undertake the Great Journey to Valinor. Their initial population included more than one-third of all Elves, evenly divided between the Tatyar and Nelyar kindreds. After their refusal, they fragmented into many separate kindreds with different languages as they spread across Middle-earth, remaining largely outside the histories preserved by the Eldar.The coming into being of the Quendi at Cuiviénen in the Year of the Trees 1050, marking the beginning of the First Age. The first Elves awoke by the shores of the inland Sea of Helcar in the far east of Middle-earth at the moment Varda finished kindling new stars in the night sky. According to tradition, the first word spoken by the Elves was ele, meaning behold, as they gazed upon the stars. The first to awaken were three pairs: Imin the First with Iminyë, Tata the Second with Tatië, and Enel the Third with Enelyë. They dwelt by the starlit waters of Cuiviénen for many Valian Years before Oromë discovered them and the Valar summoned them to Aman. The Awakening is recounted in the Cuivienyarna and represents the beginning of Elvish history and the fulfillment of Ilúvatar's design for the Firstborn Children.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Dwarves">Dwarves</a><br><br>A leader of Durin's Folk, son of Fundin and elder brother of Dwalin. Old-looking, white-bearded, and wearing a red hood when Bilbo first met him, Balin travelled with Bilbo Baggins and Gandalf on the quest to reclaim Erebor. He often served as lookout for Thorin's company and became especially fond of Bilbo, respecting the hobbit's courage and skill. After the quest he visited Bilbo in the Shire with Gandalf and spoke of the renewed prosperity of the Kingdom under the Mountain and Dale.Corrupted Maiar who followed Melkor in his rebellion and were transformed into demons of terror and flame. These powerful spirits of fire and shadow served as Morgoth's most terrible servants, dwelling in the depths of Angband and leading his armies in battle. Their true nature as fallen Ainur made them formidable adversaries even to the mightiest of the Children of Ilúvatar.The chief fortress of Sauron, standing on the Plateau of Gorgoroth in Mordor, about thirty miles east of Mount Doom and southeast of the Black Gate. It was built upon a mountain-throne above deep pits and was described as black, immensely strong, and layered with walls, battlements, and towers. Its topmost tower bore an iron crown and contained the Window of the Eye, from which Sauron watched over the land. The Sindarin name means Dark Tower, while Lugbúrz is its Black Speech name, meaning dark fortress, lock-up, or prison.A Khuzdul word meaning red, also used independently as a short name for Barazinbar, one of the three Mountains of Moria. The mountain was more commonly known in Sindarin as Caradhras and in Westron as Redhorn. As a place-name, Baraz belongs to the Dwarvish naming of the peaks above Khazad-dûm, where the red aspect of the mountain is preserved in its Khuzdul, Sindarin, and common translations. The word derives from the root B-R-Z.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>Beleg Cúthalion, meaning Strongbow, was a Sinda who served King Elu Thingol of Doriath. Together with Mablung, he was one of the great captains of the Sindar and served as captain of the Marchwardens on Doriath's northern borders. He was considered the best archer and huntsman of his time, carrying the black bow Belthronding and the arrow Dailir. Beleg became a friend and brother-in-arms of Túrin, and was known for loyalty, skill in battle, and compassion.The Great Sea, also called the Sundering Seas or Western Sea, lying west of Middle-earth and east of Aman. Before the Second Age it stretched from the Gap of Ilmen in the far north, where the Helcaraxë formed a bridge of ice between Aman and Middle-earth, to far southern waters, with its widest span near the equator and Aman forming its western edge. After the War of Wrath the sea was widened by the drowning of much land, removing the northern ice bridge. In the Downfall of Númenor the world was bent and Aman removed, and only the Straight Road led west to the Undying Lands. Its bays and islands, including the Bay of Balar and Tol Eressëa, shape the maritime geography of the Elder Days.The north-western region of Middle-earth in the First Age, once a name only for the lands near the Bay of Balar but later applied to the whole land. It lay along the Great Sea with a long western shoreline and was bounded in the east by the Ered Luin, the Blue Mountains. The River Sirion ran north to south and divided West and East Beleriand, while the Andram formed a long wall of hills across its center, and the Gelion with its tributaries drained Ossiriand in the east. Its western rivers Brithon and Nenning flowed through the Falas. In the War of Wrath most of Beleriand was drowned and only a remnant endured as Lindon, leaving its former realms and cities as memory and legend.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Men">Men</a><br><br>A Queen of Gondor and wife of King Tarannon Falastur, remembered as a Black Númenórean woman of dark reputation. She was nefarious, solitary, and loveless, disliked the sea, fish, gulls, bright colours, and elaborate adornment, and preferred the King's House in Osgiliath to Tarannon's house below Pelargir. She wore only black and silver and kept bare chambers and strange gardens set with tormented sculptures beneath cypresses and yews. Berúthiel is best known for her ten cats, nine black and one white, which she trained for secret errands and spying; their fearsome reputation preserved her name in Gondorian memory.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Men">Men</a><br><br>The eldest son of Denethor II and Finduilas, older brother of Faramir, and a commander of Gondor. Beloved by his father, he resembled Denethor in face and pride but differed from him in temperament. Boromir was strong, valiant, fair and noble of face, dark-haired and grey-eyed, with a proud and stern glance. He cared little for lore apart from tales of old battles, preferring arms and warfare. A dream shared in his household led him north to Rivendell, where he sought counsel and became one of the nine members of the Fellowship of the Ring.The pass in the Pelóri north of Taniquetil, with Tirion built upon the hill of Túna within it. It was called the Cleft of Light because the light of the Two Trees came through the gap to illuminate Eldamar, and the rocks of its walls were said to hold many jewels. After the Hiding of Valinor it remained the lone cleft through the mountains, kept open so the Elves could breathe the outer air and see the stars, and so the Vanyar and Noldor would not be wholly separated from the Teleri on the coast. The Quenya name means Light cleft, from elements for light and cleft.Elves of Light, comprising the Vanyar, Noldor, and those Teleri who completed the Great Journey and beheld the Light of the Two Trees of Valinor in the Blessed Realm. This term distinguished them from the Moriquendi who never saw that sacred light. After the return of the Noldor to Middle-earth, the Exiles found this terminology offensive to the Sindar and largely ceased its use except in written lore, preferring the terms Amanyar and Úmanyar instead.One of the mightiest peaks in the Misty Mountains and the tallest and northernmost of the three Mountains of Moria above Khazad-dûm. The Redhorn Gate ran along its southern slopes, and the peak was described as snow-tipped, sheer-sided, and red in the light of sunrise or sunset. The Dwarves called it the Cruel, a title tied to its long ill reputation. Its Sindarin name means Redhorn, formed from words for red and horn; Barazinbar, or Baraz, is the Khuzdul translation of the same name.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>One of the Sons of Fëanor, known as Caranthir the Dark. Among his brothers he was the harshest and quickest to anger. His father-name was Morifinwë, meaning Dark Finwë, for he was black-haired like his paternal grandfather, while his mother-name Carnistir referred to his ruddy complexion. His realm was in Thargelion in eastern Beleriand, where his people had much contact and trade with the Dwarves of the Blue Mountains.The southernmost of the three Mountains of Moria above the Dwarven city of Khazad-dûm, alongside Caradhras and Fanuidhol. Its Sindarin name Celebdil and Khuzdul name Zirakzigil are translated as Silvertine, with the name preserving the idea of a silver spike or sharp horn. The Endless Stair rose from the deepest halls of Khazad-dûm to Durin's Tower on its peak, giving the mountain a place in the geography of both the underworld of Moria and the high summits above it.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>One of the noblest of the Sindar, a prince of Doriath and kinsman of King Thingol. In one genealogy he was the grandson of Elmo, Thingol's brother, and therefore belonged to the royal kindred of the Sindar. In Doriath he met Galadriel of the House of Finarfin, and the two were joined in love. His Sindarin name means Silver-tall or Silver Tree, from elements connected with silver and height.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Son of Curufin, greatest of the craftsmen of Eregion and lord of the Gwaith-i-Mírdain, the People of the Jewel-smiths. As a craftsman he was second only to Fëanor his grandfather, surpassing in cunning all others who have ever wrought save Fëanor alone. In the Second Age he forged the Rings of Power in Eregion, and the Three Rings of the Elves, Vilya, Narya, and Nenya, were his own work and untouched by Sauron.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin prince and the third of the seven sons of Fëanor and Nerdanel. He was a great huntsman and a friend of the Vala Oromë, from whom he learned great skill with birds and beasts and the understanding of many of their languages. Oromë gave him the great hound Huan. Celegorm was often in the company of his brother Curufin, and the two held and fortified Himlad, including the Pass of Aglon.A land on the shores of the inland Sea of Helcar in the far east of Middle-earth, the birthplace of the Elves. Ilúvatar awakened the Quendi there in the 1050th Year of the Trees, marking the beginning of the First Age, and from the first they were divided into three kindreds: the Minyar, the Tatyar, and the Nelyar. The Elves dwelt by Cuiviénen for more than fifty Valian Years under the stars before the Valar summoned them westward in the Great Journey. Many answered the summons and became the Eldar, traveling west to Valinor, while those who refused were called the Avari and remained by the starlit waters. The Quenya name means Water of Awakening, from cuivië, awakening, and nen, water, marking it as the most sacred site in Elvish history and the source from which all the kindreds spring.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin prince, the fifth son of Fëanor and Nerdanel, and Fëanor's favorite son. He resembled his father greatly in skill, temperament, and appearance, and was the chief inheritor among his brothers of Fëanor's mastery in craftsmanship. Curufin was the father of Celebrimbor, swore the Oath of Fëanor with his brothers, and held Himlad alongside Celegorm, with whom he was closely associated.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia of Aulë the Smith, from whom he acquired great knowledge of smithing and handiwork. Chosen by Aulë to be sent to Middle-earth as chief of the Istari. His name in Quenya relates to his skill in craft and devices. At Yavanna's request, he took Aiwendil with him on the mission to Middle-earth in the Third Age.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Teleri">Teleri</a><br><br>The Shipwright, whose name means shipmaker in Sindarin, and one of the oldest and wisest of the Elves in Middle-earth. Born Nōwē and kin to both Elwë and Olwë, the kings of the Teleri, he remained in Middle-earth when his kindred departed for Valinor. He became Lord of the Falathrim, established the Havens of Brithombar and Eglarest, and was a master shipbuilder taught by Ossë. In later ages he was associated with the Grey Havens in Lindon and with the keeping of Narya, the Ring of Fire.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>A Sindarin Elf who dwelt in Doriath as the chief loremaster and minstrel of King Thingol during the First Age. He was regarded among the greatest musicians of the Elves, with Maglor named in similar esteem. Daeron devised the Cirth, the runes that were little used among the Sindar except in Menegroth, where the Dwarves learned them and later carried them east over the Blue Mountains. He loved Lúthien, daughter of Thingol and Melian, though his love was not returned.The destruction of the Two Trees of Valinor by Melkor and Ungoliant in Valian Year 1495, ending the Years of the Trees and plunging Aman into darkness. Melkor, seeking vengeance against the Valar and coveting the Silmarils, allied with Ungoliant, a primeval spirit of darkness in spider form who dwelt in Avathar. She shrouded them both in her Unlight, webs of impenetrable darkness that even the eyes of Manwë could not pierce, and together they came unseen to Ezellohar during a festival when the Valar were gathered. There Melkor struck both Telperion and Laurelin with his great spear, wounding them and causing their sap to pour forth, and Ungoliant drank greedily from the Trees, draining their light and poisoning them with her venom until they withered and died. The radiance of Valinor was extinguished, and darkness fell upon the Blessed Realm for the first time since the making of the Trees. In that same hour Melkor fled north to Formenos and murdered Finwë, stealing the Silmarils, while Ungoliant's insatiable thirst swelled her to monstrous size. The five Valian Years between the Darkening and the rising of the Sun became known as the Long Night, a time of mourning and shadow. Yavanna and Nienna tried in vain to heal the Trees, but they were beyond restoration, and only one silver flower of Telperion and one golden fruit of Laurelin remained, from which the Valar later fashioned the Moon and Sun. The Darkening marked the end of the Elder Days of Valinor and set in motion the exile of the Noldor, the Wars of Beleriand, and all the sorrows that followed from the Oath of Fëanor.A valley on the east side of the Misty Mountains beneath the Redhorn, Silvertine, and Cloudyhead peaks. It lay at the eastern end of the Redhorn Pass, was bordered by the Dimrill Stair, and held the source of the Silverlode, with Mirrormere at its southeastern corner. The Dwarves knew the valley as Azanulbizar, while its Sindarin name was Nanduhirion; both names reflect the idea of a dim valley or valley of shadowed streams. Durin the Deathless came there in ancient tradition before founding Khazad-dûm beneath the surrounding mountains, making the dale closely bound to the memory of Durin's Folk.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Half-elven">Half-elven</a><br><br>Dior Eluchíl, meaning Thingol's Heir, was the son of Beren Erchamion and Lúthien Tinúviel, and first of the Peredhil. Through his parents he was of threefold descent: from the Edain through Beren, the Eldar through Thingol, and the Maiar through Melian. Called Dior Aranel the Beautiful, he wedded Nimloth of Doriath and had three children: Eluréd, Elurín, and Elwing. He became closely associated with Menegroth and the royal inheritance of Doriath.A mighty forest kingdom of Elu Thingol, the greatest realm of the Sindar in central Beleriand. Its capital was Menegroth, and its lands were a great ring of woods about the River Sirion, including Neldoreth the northern beech forest, Nivrim the west march oaks, and the forests of Region and Radhrim; Brethil and Nan Elmoth were also held though they lay outside the later enchantment. The realm was known as the Guarded Realm and the Hidden Kingdom, for Melian's Girdle protected it and turned aside foes and wanderers. It was a cultural and political heart for the Sindar, long preserved from open war by its guarded borders and the wisdom of its king and queen.Ancient creatures of fire and malice, first brought forth by Morgoth in Angband as weapons of war and terror. Glaurung, Father of Dragons, was the first of the Fire-drakes, combining immense physical power with cunning intelligence and the ability to enchant and deceive through speech and gaze. These serpents of flame became instruments of destruction in the wars of Beleriand.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Hobbits">Hobbits</a><br><br>The second child and oldest son of Fosco Baggins and Ruby Bolger, husband of Primula Brandybuck, and father of Frodo Baggins. A regular and respectable Shire-hobbit fond of good food, Drogo often visited his generous father-in-law Gorbadoc Brandybuck at Brandy Hall and seems to have adopted some Buckland customs, including boating. His name was meaningless in contemporary Hobbitish Westron and represented an original name, Droga.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Balrog of Morgoth associated with Moria, also called the Terror and the Flame of Udûn. Originally a Maia, Durin's Bane belonged to the ancient spirits of fire and shadow that followed Morgoth. In later ages it lay deep beneath Khazad-dûm in the Misty Mountains, becoming the hidden dread of the Dwarven realm after long delving for mithril. Its name evokes the old dangers beneath Moria and the darkness that gathered around Durin's Folk.The children of Aulë the Smith, created by the Vala in his impatience for the awakening of the Children of Ilúvatar, though Eru granted them true life and independent will. Makers and craftsmen of great skill, they were given their own language Khuzdul by their creator. Seven fathers of the Dwarves were made, each founding a great house of their kindred, and they proved themselves steadfast and enduring despite not being among the original designs of Eru.<b>Disambiguation:</b><br>• Dáin I - King of Durin's Folk<br>• Dáin II Ironfoot - Lord of the Iron Hills who became King of Durin's Folk following Thorin II OakenshieldGreat Eagles or Eagles of Manwë, immense sentient birds who served as messengers and agents of the Lord of the Winds. Capable of speech and possessed of keen intelligence, these noble creatures aided the Free Peoples in their struggles against the forces of darkness. Led by mighty lords such as Thorondor, they dwelt in the high places of the world and intervened at crucial moments in the wars against Morgoth and his servants.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Ecthelion of the Fountain was an Elf-lord of Gondolin and captain of the House of the Fountain, one of the twelve houses of the Gondothlim. He possessed the most beautiful voice and greatest musical talent with the flute among all the people of the hidden city. His house and title connect him with the Fountain of the King and the noble martial traditions of Gondolin.The Elf-friends, specifically those Houses of Men who allied with the Elves during the First Age in Beleriand and fought against Morgoth. Distinguished from other Men by their friendship with the Eldar and their valor in the wars of the Silmarils, they were granted the island realm of Númenor as a reward for their faithfulness. The term particularly applies to the Three Houses who first entered Beleriand and their descendants.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Gnome-lord of Gondolin in the early version of the legendarium preserved in The Book of Lost Tales. He was leader of the folk of the Heavenly Arch, wore a blue mantle embroidered with stars of crystal, and carried a bent sword, unlike the other Noldoli. Though armed with that sword, he trusted especially to his bow and could shoot farther than anyone of his folk.The Forsaken, a group of Teleri who remained behind in the coastal regions of Middle-earth to search for their lord Thingol, who had disappeared near the end of the Great Journey. These Elves missed their chance to cross the sea to Valinor when the island ferry departed without them, and they became part of the Sindar of Beleriand, dwelling in the lands that would become the realm of Doriath.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>The wife of Angrod and mother of Orodreth, a lord of Nargothrond. She probably joined the Exile of the Noldor, since her name was translated into Sindarin in later legend, though she is not mentioned in the tales of Beleriand. Her Quenya name means Elven-flower, from Elda meaning Elf and lótë meaning flower, and its Sindarin form was Edhellos.Those Elves who accepted the summons of the Valar and began the Great Journey from Cuiviénen to Aman, even if they did not complete it. The name means "People of the Stars" and distinguishes them from the Avari who refused the call. The three kindreds of the Eldar were the Vanyar, Noldor, and Teleri, descending from the original three tribes of Minyar, Tatyar, and Nelyar.<br><br>Subdivision of the Eldar<br><br><table border="1" cellpadding="5"><tr><th colspan="3" style="text-align:left">The Three Kindreds of the Eldar</th></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><b>Vanyar</b> (from Minyar) - The Fair Elves, first to reach Aman</td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><b>Noldor</b> (from Tatyar) - The Deep Elves, masters of craft and lore</td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><b>Teleri</b> (from Nelyar) - The third kindred, most numerous and divided:<ul><li><b>Falmari</b> - Sea-elves who reached Aman</li><li><b>Sindar</b> - Grey-elves of Beleriand (includes <b>Eglath</b>, <b>Falathrim</b>, <b>Mithrim</b>)</li><li><b>Nandor</b> - Those who turned back at the Misty Mountains (includes <b>Laiquendi</b>)</li></ul></td></tr></table><i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Men">Men</a><br><br>Elendil the Tall was a Númenórean lord of the Faithful, the son of Amandil and the father of Isildur and Anárion. He was founder and first High King of the Realms in Exile, ruling over Arnor in the north and Gondor in the south. Remembered among the Dúnedain as a wise king and heroic figure, he was also notable for his great height. His Quenya name means Lover of the Stars, and among the Edain it also carried the meaning Elf-friend.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Vanyar">Vanyar</a><br><br>Wife of Turgon and mother of Idril Celebrindal. One of the Vanyar, her golden hair passed to her daughter. She is remembered as the only known full Vanya who accompanied the Flight of the Noldor, linking the usually Aman-dwelling Vanyar to the story of Turgon and Idril.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>An Elf of the royal house of the Teleri, younger brother of Elwë and Olwë. Born during the Great Journey, he remained in Beleriand and stayed close to Elwë, by whom he was beloved. Elmo is not associated with recorded deeds of his own, but he stands within the royal kindred of the Sindar and is important to the genealogy of Doriath through his descendants Celeborn and Nimloth.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Half-elven">Half-elven</a><br><br>Son of Eärendil the Mariner and Elwing the White, twin brother of Elros, and bearer of the Elven-ring Vilya. Born at the Havens of Sirion, he was one of the Half-elven and chose to be counted among the Elves. In the Second Age he established the refuge of Imladris, called Rivendell, where he dwelt as lord and master. Father of Arwen Undómiel, he was renowned for wisdom, healing, and knowledge of ancient lore.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Half-elven">Half-elven</a><br><br>Elros Tar-Minyatur, son of Eärendil the Mariner and Elwing, and twin brother of Elrond. Born at the Havens of Sirion, he was one of the Half-elven and chose to be counted among Men. He became the first King of Númenor, taking the royal name Tar-Minyatur in Quenya, meaning High First-ruler, and from him came the Line of Elros, the royal house of Númenor.The Firstborn children of Ilúvatar, who awoke at Cuiviénen under the stars. Called Quendi, "The Speakers," for they were the first to use spoken language. Immortal and bound to Arda, they divided into many kindreds through the choices they made in response to the summons of the Valar.<br><br>Subdivision of the elves<br><br><table border="1" cellpadding="5" style="width:100%"><tr><th style="text-align:left">By Journey</th></tr><tr><td><b>Eldar</b> - answered the summons</td></tr><tr><td><b>Avari</b> - refused the summons</td></tr></table><br><table border="1" cellpadding="5" style="width:100%"><tr><th style="text-align:left">By Light</th></tr><tr><td><b>Calaquendi</b> - saw the Two Trees</td></tr><tr><td><b>Moriquendi</b> - never saw the Two Trees</td></tr></table><br><table border="1" cellpadding="5" style="width:100%"><tr><th style="text-align:left">By Dwelling</th></tr><tr><td><b>Amanyar</b> - of Aman</td></tr><tr><td><b>Úmanyar</b> - not of Aman</td></tr></table><i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Half-elven">Half-elven</a><br><br>Elwing the White, daughter of Dior Eluchíl and Nimloth of Doriath, and wife of Eärendil the Mariner. She had two elder twin brothers, Eluréd and Elurín, and was the mother of the twin sons Elrond and Elros. Through her descent from Beren and Lúthien, Thingol, and Melian, she belonged to the mingled lines of Men, Elves, and Maiar. When the Valar offered the Half-elven their choice, she chose to be counted among the Elves.Ancient shepherds of the trees, placed upon Middle-earth by the will of Yavanna the Giver of Fruits in response to her concerns about the fate of growing things. These tree-like beings possessed great strength and longevity, dwelling in forests and protecting the olvar from harm. They were granted life and consciousness to serve as guardians of all that grows, though they moved slowly and spoke in a language as deep and long as the roots of mountains.A Noldorin realm in Eriador during the Second Age, also called Hollin, located west of the Misty Mountains near the West-gate of Moria. It was the only lasting Noldorin realm outside Lindon, with Ost-in-Edhil as its capital and borders marked by the Glanduin, Gwathló, Bruinen, and the cliffs near Khazad-dûm. The Elves of Eregion lived in friendship and trade with the Dwarves of Khazad-dûm, and the realm became renowned for the Gwaith-i-Mírdain, the society of jewel-smiths led by Celebrimbor. Its Sindarin name means Holly-region or Land of Holly, reflected in the Westron name Hollin.The large region in the northwest of Middle-earth between Lindon and the Blue Mountains in the west and Rhovanion and the Misty Mountains in the east, stretching roughly 675 miles east to west and 690 miles north to south. It was traversed by the Three Kindreds of the Elves on their journey to Beleriand and Valinor during the Great March, and later became home to Middle Men of Edain stock and Númenórean colonists who intermarried with the indigenous population. Its principal rivers were the Lhûn flowing through the Blue Mountains to the Gulf of Lune, the Baranduin flowing from Lake Evendim to form the eastern boundary of the Shire, and the Gwathló forming its southern border. Eriador was the setting for many of the most important events of the Second and Third Ages, including the kingdoms of Arnor and its successor states, and by the end of the Third Age its main inhabitants were the Hobbits of the Shire and the scattered remnants of the Dúnedain.The transcendent creator who exists eternally in the Timeless Halls beyond the world and bears the Flame Imperishable, the power by which true life is kindled. From his thought he brought forth the Ainur, and to teach them he set before them his theme in the form of music; as they learned to sing together, the Great Music unfolded. Out of that Music he revealed a Vision of the world and its history, and then he spoke the word “Eä,” giving being to the universe itself. Many of the Ainur entered Eä and became the Valar and the Maiar, shaping Arda according to the design shown in the Vision, while Ilúvatar remained beyond the world yet loved it and set its laws and bounds. When discord arose in the Music, he introduced new themes that could not be quenched and declared that no theme can be played that does not have its source in him, so even rebellion would be woven into a greater harmony. He is called Eru, “He that is Alone,” and Ilúvatar, “Father of All,” and the Children of Ilúvatar are the Elves and Men, the Firstborn and the Secondborn. He rarely intervenes directly, but life and fate are ultimately his gift and his design stands above all.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>One of the Valier and the wife of Irmo, dwelling with him in the Gardens of Lórien. She had the power to heal all hurts and weariness, was always clad in grey, and favored an island on the tree-shadowed lake of Lórellin where she slept during the day. In Lórien, Estë and Irmo tended to the Elves of Valinor, who drew refreshment from the fountains, and even the Valar came there for repose and ease from the burdens of Arda.The green mound at the heart of Valinor, set within the Ring of Doom near Valimar, hallowed by Yavanna and made evergreen. Upon this hill the Two Trees, Telperion and Laurelin, grew, after Yavanna sang upon the grass and Nienna watered it with her tears, and the Valar sat in council to witness the Trees' awakening. Later, Melkor and Ungoliant came to the mound and destroyed the Trees, leaving it darkened and defiled until the winds of Manwë cleared the vapours and Nienna washed the mound. The name means Green Mound, and it also bore the Quenya name Corollairë, Mound of Summer.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Half-elven">Half-elven</a><br><br>Eärendil the Mariner was one of the Half-elven, the son of Tuor and Idril, daughter of King Turgon. Raised in Gondolin during the First Age, he later lived in Arvernien by the Havens of Sirion, where he became leader of the people there. He married Elwing, daughter of Dior and descendant of Beren and Lúthien, and their sons were Elrond and Elros. With the aid of Círdan the Shipwright, Eärendil built the ship Vingilótë and was remembered as a mariner of great importance in the legends of the Elder Days.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Teleri">Teleri</a><br><br>The Swan-maiden of Alqualondë, daughter of Olwë, lord of the Teleri in Aman. Wife of Finarfin and mother of Finrod, Angrod, Aegnor, and Galadriel. Her children, being in part Sea-elves through their mother, had a love of the sea and longing for distant places, and it was partly due to this inheritance that all four chose to join the exile to Middle-earth, though Eärwen herself remained in Aman. Because of their Telerin blood through Eärwen, her children were well received in Doriath, the realm of her father's elder brother Thingol. Her name means Sea-maiden.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>Known as the Dark Elf, Eöl was a great smith who dwelt alone in the forest of Nan Elmoth in East Beleriand. Akin to Thingol and a friend of the Dwarves of Nogrod and Belegost, he learned much of their craft. He devised galvorn, a black metal of great strength and malleability, and forged the swords Anglachel and Anguirel from the iron of a fallen meteorite. His story is closely bound to Aredhel of the Noldor and their son Maeglin.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>The banner-bearer and herald of Manwë, and chief of the Maiar along with Ilmarë. He served as Manwë's messenger and representative in matters of great authority, and his role connects him closely with the power and judgment of the Elder King. His name is Quenya in form, though the ancient Loremasters knew no Elvish etymology for it and considered it probably Valarin in origin.The coastal Sindar who dwelt along the shores of Beleriand, particularly under the lordship of Círdan the Shipwright. These Grey-elves became skilled mariners and craftsmen of the sea, maintaining havens at the Falas including the ports of Brithombar and Eglarest before their destruction in the wars against Morgoth.The People of the Waves, those Teleri who completed the Great Journey and dwelt in Aman, particularly in the coastal city of Alqualondë. Expert mariners and shipwrights, they crafted the renowned white ships of the Teleri and became the greatest sailors among the Elves. They maintained a special friendship with Ossë and Uinen, the Maiar of the seas, and their lord was Olwë, brother of Thingol.One of the three peaks in the Misty Mountains above the ancient Dwarf-city of Khazad-dûm, standing with Caradhras and Celebdil as one of the Mountains of Moria. In the common tongue it was called Cloudyhead. The Dwarves used the Khuzdul name Bundushathûr, with Shathûr as a short form, and the Sindarin name Fanuidhol carries the same meaning. The names preserve the mountain's place in the layered geography and languages of Moria.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Youngest son of Finwë and his second wife Indis of the Vanyar. Husband of Eärwen daughter of Olwë, and father of Finrod, Angrod, Aegnor, and Galadriel. During the Flight of the Noldor he turned back to Valinor with a portion of his people and was afterward reckoned King of the Noldor who remained in Aman. Through Eärwen, his house had close kinship with the Teleri and with Thingol of Doriath.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin Elf, the first child and daughter of Finwë, King of the Noldor, and Indis, his second wife. She did not follow the Noldor into exile, instead abiding among the Vanyar with her mother. Her name was a combination of the names of her parents.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin princess of the First Age, daughter of Orodreth, ruler of Nargothrond, and sister of Gil-galad. She lived in Nargothrond under the rule of Finrod Felagund and was betrothed to Gwindor. He gave her the Sindarin name Faelivrin, meaning Gleam of the Sun on the Pools of Ivrin.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Second son of Finwë, born of his second wife Indis of the Vanyar, making him half-Vanyarin. Strongest and most valiant of the sons of Finwë, he became High King of the Noldor in Middle-earth. Husband of Anairë and father of Fingon, Turgon, Aredhel, and Argon, he led his people across the Helcaraxë and later helped maintain the Siege of Angband against Morgoth.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Eldest son of Fingolfin and Anairë, and later High King of the Noldor. He was renowned for his daring rescue of Maedhros, his cousin and friend, from Thangorodrim. Aided by Thorondor, the King of Eagles, Fingon freed Maedhros, and the deed helped heal the breach between the Houses of Fingolfin and Fëanor.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Eldest son of Finarfin and Eärwen, called Felagund by the Dwarves, meaning Maker of Caves. Wise, just, and powerful, he was the greatest traveler among the Eldar. He established the stronghold of Nargothrond in the Caverns of Narog, first encountered Men among Bëor's people in Ossiriand, and became a teacher and friend to the Edain, who called him Nóm, meaning Wisdom. Fairest and most beloved of the House of Finwë, he was known for loyalty, music, and friendship.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>First King of the Noldor and founder of the House of Finwë, from which branched the houses of Fëanor, Fingolfin, and Finarfin. He led his people on the Great Journey from Cuiviénen to Valinor and established the city of Tirion upon Túna in Eldamar. His first wife was Míriel, mother of Fëanor, and his second wife was Indis of the Vanyar, mother of Fingolfin and Finarfin.A stronghold in the hills of northern Valinor, built by Fëanor as his dwelling after the Valar exiled him from Tirion for threatening his half-brother Fingolfin with a sword. Finwë, who would not be parted from his eldest son, abdicated the kingship of the Noldor and went with Fëanor into exile, and there they dwelt with Fëanor's seven sons and a substantial following. The fortress was said to lie near the Halls of Mandos in the remote north, far from Valimar and Tirion, and within its strongrooms Fëanor stored a great treasury of weapons and gems. Most precious among these were the Silmarils, which he shut in a chamber of iron and kept locked away. During the festival of the Valar when Ezellohar was attacked, Melkor came secretly to Formenos and there slew Finwë, the first murder in Aman and the first death of any of the Eldar, and broke open the treasury to steal the Silmarils before fleeing to Middle-earth. The name Formenos means Northern Fortress in Quenya, from formen, north, and osto, fortress, marking it as an outpost far from the heart of Valinor's settled lands.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Eldest and most beloved son of Finwë, King of the Noldor. Greatest of the Noldor in skill of word and hand, he was renowned as a craftsman, gem-smith, and warrior. His mother Míriel named him Fëanáro, meaning Spirit of Fire. His most famous work was the creation of the Silmarils, three jewels that captured the light of the Two Trees of Valinor. He was father of seven sons and became one of the central figures among the princes of the Noldor.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>A noble Elf of Doriath, son of Elmo and therefore nephew of King Thingol and Olwë. Little is known of Galadhon himself beyond his place in the royal kindred of the Teleri and his children: Celeborn and Galathil. His name is Sindarin and appears to combine galadh, meaning tree, with the masculine suffix -on.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Daughter of Finarfin and Eärwen, and younger sister to Finrod Felagund, Angrod, and Aegnor. Received two names according to Eldar custom: her father named her Artanis meaning Noblewoman, and her mother named her Nerwen. Born in Aman as one of the Noldor, she took part in the Exile following Fëanor's rebellion. Mightiest and fairest of all the Elves that remained in Middle-earth. With her husband Celeborn, she ruled over the woodland realm of Lothlórien in later ages. Her Telerin heritage through her mother Eärwen allowed her to be well received in Doriath by her kinsman Thingol.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>A Sindarin Elf of the royal kindred of Doriath, grandson of Elmo and brother of Celeborn, Lord of Lórien. His daughter Nimloth wedded Dior, Thingol's Heir, making Galathil a distant ancestor of both Elrond and Aragorn. His name belongs to a group of names shared by his close kin and connected with the White Trees.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Gnome-lord of Gondolin in the early version of the legendarium preserved in The Book of Lost Tales. He was lord of the folk of the Tree, who wore green and probably carried either great clubs or spears. Galdor was said to be the bravest of the Gondothlim after King Turgon himself, and his name is associated with roots related to thriving and trees.The fairest of all places in Arda, the gardens of Irmo and Estë in Valinor, filled with silver willows, flowers, and quiet waters. Among its lakes is Lórellin, and the gardens are frequented by spirits who serve the Vala of visions and dreams. Nightingales sang there, and the Eldar, Maiar, and even the Valar came to rest and be refreshed by its fountains. Tilion was said to dream by the pools of Estë beneath the light of Telperion, and Melian sang there when the lights of the Two Trees mingled. Míriel also laid herself down in Lórien and released her fëa, and the name is linked to notions of slumber and dreaming.The principal river of East Beleriand, forming the western boundary of Ossiriand and draining the lands between the Ered Luin and the eastern plains. It arose from two sources, the Little Gelion from Himring and the Greater Gelion from Mount Rerir, then flowed south for many leagues, dividing Estolad from Thargelion before meeting the River Ascar near Sarn Athrad. From there it became the boundary of Ossiriand and was fed by the six other rivers of that land, growing swifter and broader after the falls; dwarves of the Blue Mountains called the lower course Gabilān. Though less wide than Sirion, it ran faster and, after joining Adurant, turned southwest to Belegaer.See <a href="bword://disambiguation.stardict?Gelmir">disambiguation page</a>.<b>Disambiguation:</b><br>• <a href="bword://Gelmir (messenger of Círdan)">Gelmir (messenger of Círdan)</a> - Noldorin Elf of Angrod's people, messenger who brought Ulmo's warning to Nargothrond with Arminas<br>• <a href="bword://Gelmir (son of Guilin)">Gelmir (son of Guilin)</a> - Brother of Gwindor, captured and tortured by Morgoth, slain at the Nirnaeth Arnoediad<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin Elf, originally one of Angrod's people, who later settled among the folk of Círdan the Shipwright in the southern regions of Beleriand. He was sent by Círdan as a messenger together with Arminas, bearing a warning from Ulmo. During their journey they encountered Tuor at the Gate of the Noldor and aided him on his path. Both Gelmir and Arminas were Calaquendi, born in Valinor before the Exile.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A noble Elf of Nargothrond, son of Guilin and brother of Gwindor. He is chiefly remembered in connection with his brother and the great wars of Beleriand. His Sindarin name is of unclear meaning, though it could combine gell, meaning joy, and mîr, meaning jewel.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>High King of the Noldor in Middle-earth during the Second Age, ruling longer than any of his predecessors. He founded a kingdom in Lindon in the far northwest of Middle-earth and was acknowledged as High King of the Elves of the West. A major ruler among the Eldar, he was closely associated with Lindon, the Elves of the West, and the great alliances of the Second Age.An Elven sword best known as Gandalf's weapon and said to have belonged to Turgon. Its Westron name was Foe-hammer, while Orcs knew it as Beater, a name remembered among the Orcs of the Misty Mountains. Glamdring was found with Orcrist and Sting in a trolls' cave in the Trollshaws, and Elrond identified it by its runes and by the Mannish name Foe-hammer. The sword had a beautiful scabbard and jewelled hilt, and like Orcrist and Sting it could glow blue in the presence of Orcs. Its Sindarin name means Foe-hammer, formed from elements associated with Orc-hosts and striking.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A noble Elf-lord of Gondolin and chief of the House of the Golden Flower, one of the mightiest warriors of the Noldor. His house bore the device of a rayed sun upon their shields, and he wore a mantle embroidered with celandines in golden threads, with arms damascened in gold. Renowned for courage and nobility, his name and house were remembered in song among the great traditions of Gondolin.The Hidden City of the Noldor in the vale of Tumladen, north of Beleriand, surrounded by the Encircling Mountains. Turgon founded it after Ulmo guided him to the secret valley, and his people, who had dwelt in Nevrast, moved there in secrecy to become the Gondolindrim. Concealed from friend and foe alike, the city was guarded by the Eagles of Thorondor and endured for nearly four hundred years as the last great Elven realm against Morgoth. Its seclusion, mountain ring, and ordered life made it legendary, until it was discovered through treachery and fell, with a few survivors escaping to the Mouths of Sirion.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>The Lord of Balrogs and High-captain of Angband, one of the foremost captains of the Dark Lord Morgoth during the First Age. He held command among Morgoth's most terrible servants and appeared in the great wars of Beleriand as a chief captain of the Balrogs. His name is associated with roots meaning dread and compulsion, force, subjection, or oppression.The westward migration of the Elves from Cuiviénen to Aman, begun at the summons of the Valar so the Eldar might dwell nearer their protection and wisdom, and so the Valar themselves might enjoy the beauty of the Firstborn. Oromë led the three clans across Middle-earth and to the Great Sea, with Ossë aiding the sea-crossing. The march produced the Sundering of the Elves, dividing the original kindreds according to who completed the journey, who turned aside, and who refused the summons. Those who reached Aman became the Amanyar, including the Vanyar and Noldor and the Falmari among the Teleri, while those who remained in Middle-earth were the Úmanyar, including the Sindar and Nandor, and those who never departed were the Avari. The journey culminated in the founding of Eldamar and reshaped Elvish history by creating lasting cultural and geographic divisions.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A lord of Nargothrond, chief of one of the four kindreds within that realm, and considered among the most noble in name and lineage. Father of Gelmir and Gwindor, both renowned for valor, he and his folk were notable contributors to the building of the deep mansions of Nargothrond. They dwelt west of the city on the slopes of Taur-en-Faroth, the Hunters' Wold.A river forming the southern border of Eriador, beginning at the confluence of the Hoarwell and Glanduin west of the Misty Mountains and flowing southwest toward the Great Sea. Near Tharbad its upper course was slow, broad, and marshy, but smaller vessels could travel up it as far as that crossing. The Númenóreans explored and used the river in the Second Age, building works at Lond Daer and later around Tharbad, where the North-South Road crossed it. The Sindarin name Gwathló means Greyflood or shadowy river from the fens, and it was also known in Adûnaic as Agathurush.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Son of Guilin and brother of Gelmir, an Elf-lord of Nargothrond betrothed to Finduilas, daughter of King Orodreth. Reckoned as a bold leader and the scout who ranged farthest afield of all the folk of Nargothrond, he belonged to one of the noble houses of that realm. His story is closely connected with Finduilas, Túrin, and the counsels of Nargothrond in the First Age.A large room in Elrond's house in Rivendell, lit by an ever-burning fire set in a great hearth between carved pillars. It stood mostly empty during the day, but at night became a place for the telling of tales and the singing of songs. Bilbo Baggins knew the hall from his stays in Rivendell, and Frodo later came there after a feast in Elrond's house, finding Bilbo at work on his poem about Eärendil. The room is associated with memory, poetry, and quiet reflection within the Last Homely House.A region of Valinor associated with Námo, the Doomsman of the Valar, who is named for his dwelling. The Halls lie westward in Valinor, near the halls of Nienna, and are described as the place to which the dead of Arda are summoned, with the fëar of Elves and Men gathered there and kept apart according to their kind. Vairë the Weaver also dwells there, recording the histories of the world in her tapestries. In Valinor's geography they stand between the far western halls and the more central regions, forming a solemn counterpoint to the Gardens of Lórien and the other blessed lands.An inland sea in the far east of Middle-earth, formed where the northern pillar of Illuin had stood after Melkor cast down the Two Lamps in the ancient days. Fed by many rivers flowing from the east, the Sea of Helcar was an enormous body of water that in some accounts stretched from the Red Mountains in the east to the Blue Mountains in the west. On its eastern shores lay Cuiviénen, the bay where the first Elves awoke under the stars and dwelt before the Great Journey. The Elves travelled north around the Sea of Helcar before turning westward toward Aman, and after their departure the sea passed largely out of history. The site of Cuiviénen lay beneath the shadows of the Orocarni, and the geography of the region was tied to the most ancient shaping of Arda before the rising of the Sun and Moon.A small race believed to be related to Men, usually between two and four feet tall, with short legs, slightly pointed ears, and furry feet with leathery soles. In early recorded history they were divided into Stoors, Fallohides, and Harfoots, whose traits later became the usual pattern among Shire-hobbits. They were generally gentle, slow to quarrel, and fond of farming, eating, pipe-weed, inns, family history, and comfortable social customs, but also showed courage, endurance, adaptability, and skill with tools, bows, and thrown stones when need arose. Their other names included Halflings among the Dúnedain, Perian in Sindarin, and Periannath in plural form.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Idril Celebrindal, only child of King Turgon of Gondolin and his Vanyarin wife Elenwë. Wife of Tuor and mother of Eärendil the Mariner, she was wise and far-seeing, with a heart often troubled by foreboding. Her union with Tuor was the second union of Elves and Men, after Beren and Lúthien, and through her the line of the Half-elven descended.One of the Two Lamps of the Valar, the northern lamp that lit Middle-earth during the Spring of Arda before the creation of the Two Trees. Wrought by Aulë, filled with light by Varda, and hallowed by Manwë, Illuin was set upon the great pillar of Helcar in the far north and shone with a blue light over the northern lands. Its pillar was taller than any mountain of the later ages, and where its light mingled with that of Ormal in the south, the lands were fairest and richest in growth. When Melkor cast down the pillar in ancient days, Illuin fell and its breaking created the inland Sea of Helcar, ending the Spring of Arda and bringing darkness and ruin to the Valar's first dwelling. The name may derive from il, sky, and luin, blue, reflecting the lamp's azure radiance.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>One of the chiefs of the Maiar and the handmaiden of Queen Varda. She is mentioned briefly in the Valaquenta alongside Eönwë, the banner-bearer and herald of King Manwë. Her name may be related to a Quenya word for starlight and to such words as Ilmen and Ilmarin.An Elven refuge and outpost in the Misty Mountains on the eastern edge of Eriador, founded by Elrond in the Second Age. Hidden in a narrow gorge of the Bruinen, it was known in the Common Speech as Rivendell and as the Last Homely House to travellers going east toward the Misty Mountains and Wilderland. Pine trees grew above the valley, with oak and beech below, and a steep zig-zag path led into the dell. Its Sindarin name means deep dale of the cleft or canyon of the cleft.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Vanyar">Vanyar</a><br><br>A Vanyarin Elf, close kin to Ingwë, King of the Vanyar, and the second wife of Finwë. She was renowned for swiftness of foot and skill at singing. With Finwë she had four children: Findis, Fingolfin, Írimë, and Finarfin. Indis did not go into exile, but abided among the Vanyar with Findis.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Vanyar">Vanyar</a><br><br>King of the Vanyar and High King of the Elves. One of the ambassadors who travelled with Oromë to the Blessed Realm, he became leader of the Vanyar during the Great March. The Vanyar first dwelt in Tirion with the Noldor, and Ingwë built the great white tower called Mindon Eldaliéva there. He later went to live on Taniquetil at the feet of Manwë.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>A Vala known as the master of visions and dreams, more commonly called Lórien after his place of dwelling. He was the younger brother of Námo, and together they were known as the Fëanturi, the masters of spirits; their sister was Nienna. Irmo lived with his spouse Estë in the Gardens of Lórien west of Valimar, where he tended and gave refuge to the Elves of Valinor through visions and dreams. His name means Desirer or Master of Desire, while Lórien means Land of Dreams.A substance made by the Elves from mithril and used by the Gwaith-i-Mírdain in constructions such as gateways. It could be seen only by reflected moonlight and starlight, and even then remained hidden until a magic word was spoken. The designs on the Doors of Durin were made from ithildin, fitting its association with secret Elven craft and guarded entrances. Gandalf translated the name as starmoon, and its Sindarin meanings are connected with moonlight, starlight, and moon-star light.The Dwarvish name for the river known to the Elves as Celebrant and to Men as the Silverlode. It rose in the eastern Misty Mountains from springs below Mirrormere in Dimrill Dale, flowed through Lothlórien, met the Nimrodel, and emptied into the Anduin. The Khuzdul name combines kibil, silver, with a second element glossed as channel, path, or rivercourse, and Tolkien Gateway notes that the name seems connected to the Dwarves' discovery of silver in the river. Its Sindarin and English names preserve the same silver-course meaning.A term for the three instances in which Elves fought and slew other Elves, all committed by the Noldor in the course of the quest to recover the Silmarils. The First Kinslaying, also called the Kinslaying at Alqualondë, took place when the Noldor seized the Telerin ships by force and Teleri were killed. The Second Kinslaying contributed to the fall of Doriath and was fought over the Silmaril held by Dior. The Third Kinslaying occurred at the Mouths of Sirion over the Silmaril borne by Elwing, and it was considered the worst of the three. These events became enduring tragedies in Eldarin memory and are treated collectively as defining wounds among the Eldar.The Green Elves or Green People, those of the Nandor who later crossed the Blue Mountains and entered Beleriand, dwelling in the land of Ossiriand. Named for their attire which was often green to blend with the forests they loved, they were skilled in woodcraft and stealth, living lightly upon the land without building great cities or kingdoms. They joined the Sindar in the wars against Morgoth, though they preserved their distinct identity and customs.The younger of the Two Trees of Valinor, called the Golden Tree, which shed golden light upon the realm of the Valar. Her leaves were edged with gold and she bore countless flowers of yellow flame upon her branches, and from her boughs fell a rain of golden dew that Varda collected in her wells. Laurelin bloomed during the second half of each Valian day, following the waning of Telperion, and her light was warm and rich like sunlight, while Telperion's was cool and silver. She grew on Ezellohar outside the gates of Valimar, watered by the tears of Nienna, and was considered the female counterpart to Telperion. When Melkor and Ungoliant destroyed the Trees in the Darkening of Valinor, one last fruit of Laurelin survived, and from this the Valar fashioned the Sun, carried aloft by the Maia Arien. Her Sindarin names included Galadlóriel, Glewellin meaning song of gold, Lasgalen meaning green of leaf, and Melthinorn meaning tree of gold.A kingdom of Silvan Elves between the south-eastern Misty Mountains and the river Anduin, with the Celebrant running through the wood. Its earliest people were Nandor who had refused to cross the Hithaeglir, and the woodland later became associated with the Galadhrim, Caras Galadhon, Celeborn, and Galadriel. In the Third Age it was considered among the most beautiful and elvish places in Middle-earth, famed for the only mallorn trees east of the sea. Its names include the Golden Wood, Lindórinand, Laurelindórenan, and other forms connected with singing, gold, and dreamlike beauty.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>Lúthien Tinúviel, meaning Nightingale, was the fairest of all the Children of Ilúvatar. Only child of Elu Thingol, King of Doriath, and Melian the Maia, she was the sole offspring of the union between one of the Ainur and one of the Elves. Through her mother she possessed powers greater than any other of the Eldar, including gifts of enchantment and song. In the woods of Neldoreth she encountered Beren, a mortal Man of the House of Bëor, and their love became the first union of Elf and Man.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>An Elf of Doriath and the chief captain of King Thingol. He was counted among the leading warriors and hunters of Thingol's realm, and is associated in the histories with Beleg and the guarded borders of Doriath. His Sindarin name means with weighted hand, from mab meaning hand and lung meaning heavy; he is also called Mablung of the Heavy Hand, Mablung the Hunter, and Thingol's chief huntsman.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Eldest of the seven sons of Fëanor and Nerdanel, and one of the chief princes of the Noldor. He was close to his cousin Fingon, whose friendship helped heal the breach between the Houses of Fingolfin and Fëanor. Maedhros later organized the Union of Maedhros, an effort to unite the peoples of Beleriand against Morgoth, and is remembered for leadership, endurance, and the burden of the Oath of Fëanor.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Son of Eöl the Dark Elf and Aredhel, sister of Turgon. Born in Nan Elmoth, he came with his mother to Gondolin and became mighty among its people. Skilled in mining and smithcraft, he searched for ore in the mountains and held a notable place in the hidden city. His story is closely bound to the houses of Eöl, Aredhel, Turgon, and Idril.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>The second of the sons of Fëanor, known for poetry and singing. In Tirion he swore the Oath of Fëanor, and later composed the Noldolantë, the Fall of the Noldor, in memory of the sorrows connected with that oath. In Beleriand his ward was the open region between the arms of the Gelion River, which became known as Maglor's Gap.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin Elf, skilled smith of Valinor, and father of Nerdanel, the wife of Fëanor. He learned the arts of metalwork and stonecraft under Aulë and was called an Aulendur, a Servant of Aulë. Mahtan was fond of copper, wore a copper circlet, and was known as Urundil, meaning Copper-lover. He taught Fëanor smithcraft, though he later regretted how that knowledge was used. Mahtan was also unusual among Elves for having a beard early in his second cycle of life.Spirits whose being began before the world, of the same order as the Valar but of lesser degree and power. These lesser Ainur served the greater Valar and fulfilled many roles in the shaping and governance of Arda, from tending the gardens of Lórien to bearing messages across great distances. Some, like Olórin and Curumo, would later be sent to Middle-earth in different forms, while others like Melian dwelt among the Children of Ilúvatar. Yet as beings of free will, some fell into darkness and became servants of Melkor.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>The Doomsman of the Valar, one of the Aratar. His true name is Námo, meaning Judge or Ordainer in Quenya, though he is more commonly called Mandos after his dwelling place. He pronounces judgment at the bidding of Manwë and is keeper of the Houses of the Dead. Numbered among the Fëanturi with his brother Irmo, he is husband to Vairë the Weaver, whose tapestries line the halls of his realm. He knows and remembers nearly all things that were and shall be, except those still lying in the freedom of Ilúvatar.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>Manwë Súlimo, the Elder King, King of the Valar, and High King of Arda. Dearest to Eru and closest to his mind, he was appointed Ruler of Arda and vicegerent on Earth. His attributes are air, winds, and the birds, which serve him and bring news from the farthest and deepest places of the world. He dwells with Varda atop Taniquetil, the highest mountain of the world, and together they can see farther than all other eyes. Manwë is a kind and compassionate ruler, unconcerned with his own power, and bears a sapphire sceptre made for him by the Noldor.<b>Disambiguation:</b><br>• Book of Mazarbul<br>• Chamber of Mazarbul in Moria<br>• mazarbul - a Khuzdul word<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia who dwelt in the Gardens of Lórien in Valinor, tending its trees. Most beautiful, wise, and skilled in songs of enchantment among all the people of Irmo, she also served Vána and Estë. In Middle-earth she encountered Elwë of the Teleri in Nan Elmoth; they wed, and she became Queen of Doriath, the only known Ainu to take one of the Children of Ilúvatar as spouse. She bore Lúthien Tinúviel and shrouded Doriath in the Girdle of Melian, an invisible barrier of magic and mystery.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Ainur">Ainur</a><br><br>Greatest and most powerful of all the Ainur created by Eru Ilúvatar, though he fell from glory and was cast out from the company of the Valar. In the Music of the Ainur he wove discord into the Theme of Ilúvatar, and when he entered Arda he claimed mastery over it. His power at the beginning was greater than that of any other Vala, and he corrupted many Ainur to his service, marred Arda, and waged war against the Valar and the Children of Ilúvatar. He was later named Morgoth Bauglir, meaning Dark Enemy or Black Foe of the World.The Secondborn children of Ilúvatar, mortal beings who awoke in Hildórien when the Sun first rose, long after the Firstborn Elves. Granted the gift of mortality and freedom from the Music of the Ainur, their fate lay beyond the circles of the world in a mystery known only to Eru. Unlike the immortal Elves bound to Arda until its ending, Men would leave the world after death, though the shadow of Morgoth's corruption touched them early, and many fell under the dominion of darkness before ever meeting the Eldar.The Thousand Caves, an underground city of Doriath above the River Esgalduin, home to King Thingol and Queen Melian. It was a cavern town hewn into a rocky hill by the Dwarves of Belegost, with its only entrance by gates high above the river and a stone bridge spanning a deep ravine. Within were vast halls and the Menelrond where Thingol's throne stood. The pillars were shaped like beeches with branches and leaves, the halls were lit by golden lanterns and silver fountains, and the caves held carvings and figurines of animals. It became the most beautiful palace east of the Sea and the royal heart of the Sindar.The central continent of Arda, lying east of Belegaer and west of the Land of the Sun across the East Sea. Most of the history of Arda takes place here, and it is where the Children of Ilúvatar, Elves and Men, came into being along with the Dwarves. In the Elder Days the inland seas of Helcar and Ringil lay to the north and south of its center after the fall of the Two Lamps. The Westlands are the best known portion: their western part, Beleriand, was drowned at the end of the First Age, and survivors relocated to Lindon and Eriador beyond the Blue Mountains. The continent is also called Endor or Ennorath in Elvish tongues.A dark, still lake in Dimrill Dale on the east side of the Misty Mountains, less than a mile below the East-gate of Khazad-dûm. It was long and oval like a spear-head, with deep blue water and a surface famous for its mirror-like stillness. Near its southern end stood Durin's Stone, marking the place where Durin the Deathless, according to the Dwarves of Durin's Folk, looked into the lake and saw a crown of stars reflected above his head before founding Khazad-dûm beneath the surrounding mountains. Its Khuzdul name Kheled-zâram probably means glass-pool or glass-lake.A reviving cordial associated with the Valar and the Elves. Miruvórë was a mead or nectar of the Valar, poured at festivals in Valinor, though the Elves did not know its ingredients or making. Miruvor, a reduced form of the same word, was also the name of a cordial made in Rivendell, probably based on honey from scented flowers. Known as the Cordial of Imladris, it was used to restore strength in cold and hardship. The word is Sindarin, borrowed from Quenya miruvórë, and ultimately comes from a Valarin word for honey wine.A precious metal, also called Moria-silver, silver-steel, or true-silver, prized for strength, lightness, malleability, and untarnishing silver beauty. The Dwarves had their own secret name for it, while the Elves called it mithril, a Sindarin name from words meaning grey or light grey and brilliance. It was found in the Misty Mountains in lodes running north from Moria toward Caradhras and into the dark, and was also associated with Númenor and probably Aman. The sole mithril-vein of the Misty Mountains made the Longbeards of Moria wealthy, and the Noldor of Eregion used the metal in works such as ithildin, the starmoon alloy on the Doors of Durin.Sindar who dwelt in the region around Lake Mithrim in northern Beleriand, among the Grey-elves who had remained in Middle-earth during the Great Journey. They witnessed the return of the Noldor and the rising of the Moon and Sun, dwelling in lands that would become crucial in the wars against Morgoth.The grandest mansion of the Dwarves, delved through the central Misty Mountains so widely that by the Second Age a traveller could pass through it from west to east. Founded in ancient days by Durin near Azanulbizar and Mirrormere, Khazad-dûm grew into a vast underground city of gates, halls, levels, deeps, mines, and bridges over dark chasms. Its wealth was bound especially to mithril, and its fame reached even the distant Elves of Beleriand. Moria is Sindarin for Black Chasm or Black Pit, while its Westron name Phurunargian means Dwarrowdelf or Dwarf-delving.Elves of Darkness, all those who did not behold the Light of the Two Trees of Valinor, including the Avari and initially the Sindar. The term was used by the Eldar of Aman to distinguish those who had seen the sacred light from those who had not. However, the Noldorin Exiles discovered that the Sindar found this term offensive, leading to a shift toward the geographic terms Amanyar and Úmanyar, with Moriquendi eventually being reserved primarily for the Avari and lesser-known Elven peoples.A court near Valimar where the Valar held their councils, described as a circle filled with their thrones. It lay outside Valimar's western gates, and within its ring stood the green mound of Ezellohar, where the Two Trees once grew. The Valar sat there to witness Yavanna's song that awakened the Trees, and thereafter they held their great councils bathed in their light. The Ring of Doom is thus a central place of judgment and decision in Valinor, associated with the most momentous choices in the history of Eä. The Quenya name Máhanaxar is tied to the idea of authority and a ring.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Míriel Þerindë, also spelled Serindë, was the first wife of Finwë, King of the Noldor, and the mother of Fëanor. She was devoted to crafts, unsurpassed in weaving and needlework, and her mother-name means the Broideress in reference to her marvelous dexterity of hand. Her name may mean Jewel-daughter, and her hair was described as silver in appearance, an unusual colour for one of the Noldor.Those Elves who turn back, Teleri who refused to cross the Misty Mountains during the Great Journey and instead remained in the valley of Anduin. Led initially by Lenwë, they wandered in the wild lands east of the mountains, eventually spreading throughout the forests of Middle-earth. Some of their number, the Laiquendi, would later cross into Beleriand, but most remained in the eastern lands, their histories largely unrecorded in the annals of the Eldar.A stronghold built by Finrod Felagund and delved into the banks of the River Narog in West Beleriand. Its deep halls and armouries were carved after the fashion of Menegroth, forming a hidden fortress and royal seat. It became the capital of a realm between the rivers Nenning, Narog, and Teiglin, including Taur-en-Faroth, Talath Dirnen, and Tumhalad, and Finrod was overlord of the Elves of West Beleriand except the Falathrim. Its underground architecture, river setting, and broad realm made it one of the greatest Noldorin centers of power and refuge in the First Age.The chief river of West Beleriand and the largest tributary of Sirion, rising from the Pools of Ivrin in the Ered Wethrin. From its source it flowed south and then southeast, passing through a gorge and rapids as it crossed the Andram, before meeting Sirion in Nan tathren not far above the Mouths of Sirion. Its principal tributaries were the Ginglith and the Ringwil, and just south of the Ringwil's inflow the city of Nargothrond was carved into its western bank. The Narog's swift course, rapids, and gorge shaped the landscape of western Beleriand and the defenses of its great Noldorin stronghold.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Dwarves">Dwarves</a><br><br>A great Dwarven craftsman of Khazad-dûm during the height of its glory. He was renowned for his craft and formed a friendship with Celebrimbor, the Elf-lord and master artificer of neighbouring Eregion. Together they made the mighty Doors of Durin, which guarded the West-gate of the Dwarven city. Narvi stands as one of the few named Dwarven artisans closely associated with the shared craft of Khazad-dûm and Eregion.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Men">Men</a><br><br>Sauron's most feared servants in Middle-earth: mortal Men who received Nine Rings of Power and were gradually drawn into the domination of the One Ring, fading into wraiths. In the Third Age they reappeared as agents of Sauron, bringing dread through their presence and riding in black cloaks while searching for the Ring. Their chief was the Witch-king of Angmar, and Khamûl was the only other one named in Tolkien's writings. The Black Speech name means Ringwraiths.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Daughter of Mahtan the smith and wife of Fëanor. A skilled sculptor, she made statues so lifelike that people thought them real and tried to speak to them. Known as Nerdanel the Wise, she was strong-willed, free of mind, filled with desire for knowledge, and more patient than her husband. She bore Fëanor seven sons: Maedhros, Maglor, Celegorm, Caranthir, Curufin, Amrod, and Amras, an unusually large family among the Eldar.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>One of the Valier, sister of Oromë and wife of Tulkas. Lithe and fleet of foot, she is swift as an arrow and can outrun the deer who follow her in the wild. She is renowned for dancing upon the ever-green lawns of Valimar. Her name means young in Quenya, and she wed Tulkas upon the Isle of Almaren.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>A Queen of the Valar, sister of Mandos and Irmo, and one of the Aratar. She is acquainted with grief and sorrow, but also with pity and courage, and mourns for the wounds of the world caused by evil. Those who listen to her learn wisdom and endurance in grief. Nienna dwells alone in the distant west, close to the Halls of Mandos, and goes there often to comfort and counsel those in the Halls of Waiting. She wears a grey hood, and her name contains the Quenya word nie, meaning tear. Olórin learned much from her.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>An Elf-maiden of Doriath, daughter of Galathil. She wedded Dior Eluchíl, heir of King Thingol, and for a time they dwelt by the waterfall of Lanthir Lamath at the base of the Blue Mountains. She bore three children: the twin sons Eluréd and Elurín, and a daughter, Elwing. Her Sindarin name means White Blossom.The fifth battle of the Wars of Beleriand, fought between the forces of Morgoth and the Union of Maedhros, and named for the words of the Doom of Mandos: "Tears unnumbered ye shall shed." After the Dagor Bragollach, the Noldor had lost the entire north and were largely reduced to Hithlum and Nargothrond, and the Union attempted a coordinated offensive to break Morgoth's power. The plan divided the Union into two hosts, a western host under Fingon and an eastern host under Maedhros, hoping to strike like hammer and anvil when a beacon was lit in Dorthonion; Turgon came unexpectedly with a host from Gondolin. Morgoth learned of the plan through spies, and treachery among Men ruined the coordination. The battle ended in heavy losses for the Elves, leaving Morgoth dominant over Beleriand. The slain were piled into Haudh‑en‑Nirnaeth, the Hill of the Slain, and the defeat shaped the grim course of the remaining First Age.The Deep Elves or Wise, the second of the three kindreds of the Eldar, descending from the Tatyar who accepted the summons to Aman. Most skilled among the Elves in crafts and lore, they were beloved of Aulë the Smith who taught them much. Generally possessing dark hair of brown or black, they were led by Finwë to Valinor where they founded the great city of Tirion. Their insatiable thirst for knowledge and creation would eventually lead to their rebellion and return to Middle-earth in pursuit of the Silmarils.A great island kingdom of the Second Age, the realm of the Dúnedain, set in the Great Sea between Middle-earth and Aman. The land was raised from the sea by Ossë as a gift to the Edain, and it was called Elenna, the Starwards, because the Edain were led to it by the Star of Eärendil and because the island was shaped like a five-pointed star. Its promontories were Forostar, Andustar, Hyarnustar, Hyarrostar, and Orrostar, with the central region of Mittalmar and the holy mountain Meneltarma at its heart. Númenor had only two rivers, Siril and Nunduinë, and its chief city was Armenelos, alongside ports such as Andúnië and Rómenna.The terrible and irrevocable oath sworn by Fëanor and his seven sons at Tirion after learning of the theft of the Silmarils and the murder of Finwë, binding them to pursue with vengeance and hatred anyone in Arda, whether Vala, Elf, Man, Maia, or even one of their own kin, who should take or withhold a Silmaril from them. Fëanor spoke the oath in the name of Ilúvatar, calling upon Manwë and Varda as witnesses and invoking everlasting darkness upon himself and his sons should they fail or falter, and his seven sons, Maedhros, Maglor, Celegorm, Caranthir, Curufin, and the twins Amrod and Amras, swore the same dreadful vow. The oath became a curse upon the House of Fëanor, driving them to commit kinslaying and atrocity in their relentless pursuit of the jewels: the First Kinslaying at Alqualondë where they slew the Teleri for their ships, the Second Kinslaying at Doriath where they attacked Dior Eluchíl and his people, and the Third Kinslaying at the Mouths of Sirion where they assaulted the refugees led by Elwing. The oath bound them even beyond death, as Mandos would not release the spirits of the sons of Fëanor from his halls while their oath remained unfulfilled. Of the seven sons, only Maedhros and Maglor survived to see the end of the First Age, and when they seized the last two Silmarils after the War of Wrath, the jewels burned their hands in judgment of their evil deeds. In despair, Maedhros cast himself with his Silmaril into a fiery chasm, and Maglor threw his into the sea, thus ending the oath in tragedy and loss. The Oath of Fëanor stands as one of the great calamities of the Elder Days, a rash vow that brought ruin to its swearers and to countless innocents, and its shadow fell upon all the long years of the Wars of Beleriand.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Teleri">Teleri</a><br><br>Lord of Alqualondë and king of the Teleri in Aman, also known as the Falmari. Younger brother of Elwë, who became Thingol of Doriath, he led the Teleri who completed the Great Journey to Valinor after his brother remained in Beleriand. He built Alqualondë, the greatest city of the Teleri on the shores of Aman, and was father of Eärwen, who wed Finarfin.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia of Valinor, later known in Middle-earth as Gandalf. He was counted among the wisest of the Maiar and was associated with Manwë, Varda, Irmo, and Nienna. In his youth he dwelt in Lórien, and his ways often took him to the house of Nienna, from whom he learned pity and patience. In the Third Age he was sent to Middle-earth by the Valar as one of the Istari.An Elven sword and the mate of Glamdring, with a decorated scabbard and jewelled hilt. Like Glamdring and Sting, it could warn its bearer of Orcs by glowing blue, and Orcs called it Biter because of the fear attached to it among their kind. It was found in a trolls' cave in Eriador with Glamdring and Sting, then identified by Elrond. The blade became associated with Thorin Oakenshield during the Quest of Erebor. Its Sindarin name means Goblin-cleaver, and Tolkien Gateway connects it with sword-name elements related to rending or slashing.Creatures of Morgoth, twisted and corrupted beings created by the Dark Lord as foot soldiers in his wars against Elves and Men. According to some accounts, the first Orcs were made by capturing Elves and torturing them in the darkness until they were transformed into these monstrous forms, though their true origin remained a matter of debate among the wise. Bred for malice and destruction, they served the purposes of darkness throughout the ages.One of the Two Lamps of the Valar, the southern lamp that lit Middle-earth during the Spring of Arda before the creation of the Two Trees. Wrought by Aulë, filled with light by Varda, and hallowed by Manwë, Ormal was set upon the great pillar of Ringil in the far south and shone with a golden light over the southern lands. Its pillar stood taller than any mountain of later ages, and where its golden light mingled with the blue radiance of Illuin in the north, the Great Lake and the Isle of Almaren lay, and there the Valar made their first dwelling. When Melkor cast down the pillar at least five ages before the beginning of the First Age, Ormal fell and its breaking created the Sea of Ringil in the south, ending the Spring of Arda and forcing the Valar to retreat to Aman. The name apparently means Lofty Gold or High Gold, reflecting the lamp's golden radiance.A mountain range in the far northeast of Middle-earth, made by the Valar after Melkor destroyed the Two Lamps and called the Red Mountains in the common tongue. Cuiviénen lay on the shores of a bay at the eastern end of the inland Sea of Helcar, near the feet of the Orocarni, and it was here beneath the shadow of these eastern peaks that the first Elves awoke under the stars. The Quenya name is a compound of oro, mountain, and the plural of carnë, red, marking these heights as the Mountains of the East in the most ancient geography of Arda. The range stood as a boundary of the known lands in the Elder Days, and little is told of what lay beyond them in the uttermost east.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Son of Angrod, lord of the Noldor, and a dynast of the House of Finarfin. He served as warden of Minas Tirith under his uncle Finrod and later became King of Nargothrond. Father of Finduilas and Gil-galad, he belongs to the royal lineage linking the House of Finarfin with the great hidden realm on the River Narog.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>The Huntsman of the Valar and the Great Rider, one of the Aratar. He was a hunter of monsters and evil creatures, riding upon his steed Nahar and blowing his great horn Valaróma. Oromë loved horses, hounds, trees, and forests, and in Yavanna's woods in Valinor he trained his folk and beasts to hunt the evil creatures of Melkor. He was the brother of Nessa and husband of Vána, and was the first among the Valar to find the Elves at Cuiviénen. He gave them the name Eldar and accompanied them from Cuiviénen to Beleriand.A wooded region of eastern Beleriand between the Ered Luin and the River Gelion, bounded by Ascar to the north and Adurant to the south, named for the seven rivers that watered it. It was settled by the Nandor under Denethor, who became known as the Green elves, skilled in woodcraft and secrecy; the Noldor called the land Lindon, the Land of Music, for the singing heard across the Gelion. Elm trees were plentiful, and the region remained lightly peopled and largely untouched by the great wars, later surviving the War of Wrath as the remnant land known afterward as Lindon.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia of the Inner Seas associated with Ulmo, loving the winds and preferring the coasts and isles of Middle-earth to the deeps. He was the spouse of Uinen. During the early days of Arda, Ossë turned to Melkor for a time, but Uinen brought him back to loyalty to Ulmo. Some darkness and violence remained in his spirit, and he enjoyed raging in storms despite Ulmo's will, while only Uinen could restrain his wild urges. He befriended the Lindar during the Great March, taught them sea-lore and sea-music, and in the Second Age raised the island of Númenor from the depths.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia associated with Oromë and friend of Alatar, who took him along when chosen for the mission to Middle-earth as one of the Istari. The two were known as the Blue Wizards and journeyed into the far East and South of Middle-earth, where they were sent to contest the will of Sauron. Pallando is a Quenya name that may contain the element palan-, meaning far.The great mountain fence of Aman, raised by the Valar after the destruction of Almaren to defend their new realm against Melkor. The range forms the eastern wall of Valinor, with the Light of the Two Trees shining behind it while the narrow shores at its eastern feet lay in shadow. The tallest peak is Taniquetil, where the mansions of Manwë and Varda stand; the second highest is Hyarmentir above Avathar. The Valar later cut the Calacirya through the mountains so the Light could reach Eldamar and Tol Eressëa, and the mountains were raised higher during the Nurtalé Valinóreva.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A loremaster of the Noldor, born in Nevrast to a Sindarin and a Noldorin parent, whose Sindarin name means teaching sage or doctor of lore. When Turgon built Gondolin, Pengolodh moved with the people there and became one of its great scholars. He was a member of the Lambengolmor and was known as the Sage of the Noldor, counted as the greatest loremaster since Fëanor and Rúmil. The Annals of Beleriand are attributed to him, as are the edited Annals of Valinor, furthering the work of Rúmil.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Gnome-lord of Gondolin in the early version of the legendarium preserved in The Book of Lost Tales. He was marshal of both the House of the Pillar and the House of the Tower of Snow, and was described as the tallest of the Gnomes. His name is Gnomish, though its meaning is not glossed; its Qenya cognate was Pendelot.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Gnome-lord of Gondolin in the early version of the legendarium preserved in The Book of Lost Tales. Rog was a blacksmith and chief of the folk of the Hammer of Wrath. He was considered the strongest of the Noldoli and among the greatest in valour. His name appeared earlier as Rôg, while the early Gnomish Lexicon gives rog as doughty or strong; its Qenya form was Rōka.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin sage of Tirion, one of the Lambengolmor, the Loremasters of the Noldor, and the first deviser of written characters among the Elves. In the days of bliss in Valinor, he invented a writing system fitting for recording speech and song, creating letters both for graving upon metal or stone and for drawing with brush or pen. His alphabet was called the Tengwar of Rúmil, or Sarati, meaning "letters," as each character was called a sarat. This system was later expanded and perfected by Fëanor into the Tengwar of Fëanor, more commonly known simply as Tengwar. Very learned in languages, he studied the secret tongue of the Valar through the teaching of Aulë. To him is attributed the authorship of the earliest annals and lore of the Elder Days, including accounts of the Ainulindalë and the early history of Arda. His chronicles preserved the oldest traditions of the creation of the world and the doings of the Valar and Eldar in the ancient days.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Nandor">Nandor</a><br><br>A counsellor at the court of King Thingol in Doriath, of the Guest-elves: Green-elves or Nandor who sought refuge in the hidden kingdom. His father Ithilbor was chief of the Guest-elves and held a permanent seat in Thingol's council. Proud and resentful, Saeros begrudged the honour and esteem that Thingol showed to Túrin, the human foster son of the king.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia who entered Arda with Ulmo. Salmar was the maker of the Ulumúri, the great horns of Ulmo, which produce the music of the sea. In the early version of the legendarium preserved in The Book of Lost Tales, Salmar was also called Noldorin and was counted as a Vala, but in the later account he is a Maia associated with Ulmo.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia of Aulë the Smith, mightiest of that Vala's people, originally called Mairon, meaning The Admirable in Quenya. From Aulë he learned much of smithing and handiwork, becoming a great craftsman and mighty in lore. Coveting power through which he would coordinate all things according to his own will, he was ensnared by Melkor in the Spring of Arda and became his greatest and most trusted servant. By the time the Elves awoke, he had command over Angband as Melkor's lieutenant.Men, the younger children of Ilúvatar who awoke in Middle-earth millennia after the Elves, when the Sun first rose in the heavens. So named by the Firstborn to distinguish the two races of the Children, though the Secondborn were granted gifts and destinies different from their elder kindred, including the mystery of mortality and freedom from the circles of the world.The three supreme jewels of Arda, wrought by Fëanor in Aman during the Years of the Trees from the crystalline substance silima, into which he captured and preserved the mingled light of Telperion and Laurelin. The Silmarils shone with their own inner light, brighter than the stars, and were the most beautiful works ever made by the Children of Ilúvatar, surpassing all other gems in radiance and holiness. Fëanor gave his heart to their making and could never duplicate them, and after the Darkening of Valinor they alone contained the last unmarred light of the Two Trees. Varda hallowed the Silmarils so that no mortal flesh nor any hands defiled by evil could touch them without being scorched and withered, making them sacred and untouchable to the unworthy. When Melkor murdered Finwë and stole the jewels from Formenos, Fëanor and his seven sons swore the terrible Oath of Fëanor, vowing to pursue anyone who withheld a Silmaril from them, even unto everlasting darkness, and this oath brought ruin and kinslaying upon the Noldor. The theft ignited the Wars of Beleriand and the long struggle against Morgoth, who set the Silmarils in his Iron Crown though they burned his hands black. Beren and Lúthien recovered one Silmaril from Morgoth's crown, and it passed through Dior and Elwing to Eärendil, who bore it on his brow as he sailed the skies as a star of hope. After the War of Wrath, Maedhros and Maglor seized the two remaining Silmarils, but found themselves burned by them due to their evil deeds, and in anguish Maedhros cast himself and his jewel into a chasm of fire while Maglor threw his into the sea. Thus the three Silmarils endure forever sundered: one in the heavens with Eärendil, one in the fires of the earth, and one in the depths of the sea, their light present in all the elements but beyond the reach of mortal hands.The Grey-elves, those Teleri who began the Great Journey to Valinor but remained in Beleriand, never crossing the sea to the Blessed Realm. Many stayed to search for their lord Thingol who had disappeared, enchanted by Melian in the forests of Nan Elmoth. Under Thingol and Melian they established the great kingdom of Doriath and other realms in Beleriand, becoming a mighty people skilled in song and starlight, though they had never seen the Light of the Two Trees. They developed their own culture and language, distinct from both the Avari and the Calaquendi.A stream in Eriador whose name means stream of the Gate. It flowed from springs near the Doors of Durin, the West-gate of Moria, and followed the highroad toward Eregion and Ost-in-Edhil. Before the West-gate it ran through a shallow valley, dropped through a wide cleft over the Stair Falls, and continued as a swift, noisy stream through a deep narrow channel. Its bed was marked by brown and red stained stones, with the highroad running on its northern side.The principal river of Beleriand, running from the Eithel Sirion beneath the Ered Wethrin southward to the Bay of Balar, and for much of its length forming the border between East and West Beleriand. From its source it passed through the Fen of Serech and the narrow Pass of Sirion between the Ered Wethrin and the Echoriath, then continued south past Brethil and Doriath before plunging underground at the Falls of Sirion in the Andram and emerging at the Gates of Sirion. It flowed through Nan tathren to its mouths, receiving many tributaries including the Taeglin, Esgalduin, Aros, and Narog. The river's crossings and islands, such as Tol Sirion, were strategic points in the wars of the First Age.A period of peace and flourishing in Arda during the Days before Days, beginning after the First War ended and the Two Lamps were raised. Yavanna's seeds grew and spread, filling the lands with trees and herbs, beasts and birds, and all the world became green under the light of Illuin in the north and Ormal in the south. At the midmost of Arda lay the Great Lake and the Isle of Almaren, where the light of the Two Lamps mingled and living things were richest in growth and fairest in hue, and there the Valar made their first dwelling and rested after their labors. The Spring endured until Melkor returned in war and cast down the pillars of the Lamps in the 3450th Valian Year, breaking the lands, roiling the seas, and bringing darkness to Middle-earth. The destruction marked the end of the first blissful age and drove the Valar to retreat to Aman, where they later made the Two Trees.An Elven knife, probably made in Gondolin in the First Age, whose maker and first bearer are unknown. Bilbo Baggins claimed it from the treasure in the trolls' cave during the Quest of Erebor, and it later became a chief weapon of Bilbo and Frodo Baggins. Small by the standards of Men or Elves, it served as a short sword for a Hobbit. Sting glowed blue near Orcs and goblins, proved useful in dark places and against spider-webs, and received its name after Bilbo used it against the spiders of Mirkwood.Anar, the Sun, was made from the last fiery fruit of Laurelin after the destruction of the Two Trees. Set in a vessel made by Aulë and his people and steered by the Maia Arien, it first rose in the west because Valinor lay in the West of the World; the Valar later set its course from east to west across Middle-earth. Elvish names included Anar and Anor, the common Sindarin form seen in Minas Anor and Anórien. Other names included Vása, Kalantar, Daystar, and Gollum's Yellow Face.A tributary of Sirion, rising in the Ered Wethrin and flowing southeast through Brethil before joining Sirion on the borders of Doriath. In its upper course it ran through the Ravines of Taeglin along the forest's edge, and farther south it could be forded at the Crossings of Taeglin. A road ran through the valley from Nargothrond toward Minas Tirith, making it a route of travel and war. The name reflects a sense of boundary, and earlier writings used the form Teiglin before the later spelling Taeglin was adopted.The highest peak of the Pelóri and the tallest mountain in Arda, a holy mountain in central Aman. On its summit stood Ilmarin, the mansions of Manwë and Varda, from which they looked out over the world. The mountain bore many names, including Oiolossë, Ever snow white, and Amon Uilos, White Mountain, and its Quenya name is glossed as High White Peak or High snow peak. It was raised in Aman in the Valian Years and became a symbol of the West's majesty and the seat of the highest authority among the Valar.The third and most numerous of the three kindreds of the Eldar, descending from the Nelyar who accepted the summons to Aman. During the Great Journey they became most scattered and divided, as many of their number turned aside or remained behind. Those who completed the journey to Valinor became the Falmari, master mariners of the coast of Eldamar, while those who remained in Middle-earth became the Sindar under Thingol. The Nandor who turned back at the Misty Mountains and the Laiquendi who later entered Beleriand were also of Telerin origin.The elder of the Two Trees of Valinor, called the White Tree or the Silver Tree, which shed silver light upon the realm of the Valar. His leaves were dark green above and shining silver beneath, and his boughs were decked with brilliant flowers that shed a rain of silver dew, collected as a source of water and light. Telperion bloomed during the first half of each Valian day, followed by Laurelin, and his light was cool and pale like moonlight, while Laurelin's was warm and golden. He grew on Ezellohar outside the gates of Valimar, created by Yavanna and watered by the tears of Nienna, and was considered the male counterpart to Laurelin. When Melkor and Ungoliant destroyed the Trees in the Darkening of Valinor, one last flower of Telperion survived, and from this the Valar fashioned the Moon, carried aloft by the Maia Tilion. Because the Elves especially loved Telperion, Yavanna made Galathilion, an image of Telperion that stood in Tirion and gave rise to the line of White Trees that descended through Celeborn to Nimloth of Númenor and ultimately to the White Tree of Gondor.A ford and fortified town on the river Gwathló at the southern border of Eriador. It stood a few miles downstream from the meeting of the Hoarwell and Glanduin, where the upper Gwathló spread into marshland, and became a key crossing for the North-South Road between Arnor and Gondor. The Númenóreans and later the kingdoms in exile drained land, built dykes, a bridge, forts, causeways, and river works around the site, making it a strategic port and road-crossing. In later centuries the bridge and road declined, the region returned toward fenland, and Tharbad became known as a perilous ruin and ford. Its Sindarin name means road-crossing or stepping stones.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>Originally called Elwë, one of the two leaders of the Teleri during the Great Journey from Cuiviénen, along with his younger brother Olwë. In Beleriand he encountered Melian, one of the Maiar, in the forest of Nan Elmoth, and alone among the Children of Ilúvatar he married one of the Ainur. Known thereafter as Elu Thingol in Sindarin, he became High King of the Sindar and founded Doriath. Father of Lúthien Tinúviel, he ruled a realm protected by Melian's power.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Dwarves">Dwarves</a><br><br>Thorin II, called Thorin Oakenshield, was King of Durin's Folk, son of Thráin II, grandson of Thrór, and elder brother of Frerin and Dís. After the dragon Smaug drove the Dwarves of Erebor into exile, Thorin lived among Durin's Folk in the Blue Mountains and became their leader. His epithet Oakenshield came from the Battle of Azanulbizar, where he used a branch of oak as a shield after his own was broken. In T.A. 2941 he led the Quest of Erebor with twelve Dwarves, Bilbo Baggins, and Gandalf, seeking the recovery of the Lonely Mountain. He was a proud and formidable Dwarf-lord, associated with the heirlooms and hopes of the House of Durin.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia who guided the Moon. In the days of the Trees in Valinor, Tilion was a hunter from the company of Oromë and often rode with him, though he spent much of his free time in Lórien under the light of Telperion. He loved silver, used a silver bow, and begged to be given the care of the Moon. He was less mighty than Arien, the Maia chosen to guide the Sun, and was drawn by her splendour; reckless at times, he did not always follow the correct path.The city of the Eldar in Eldamar, built on the green hill of Túna within the Calacirya, the only pass through the Pelóri. Its white walls and terraces crowned the hill, and its streets were said to be strewn with white sand like grains of diamond, with crystal stairs rising to its gates. The city was dominated by Ingwë's tower, the Mindon Eldaliéva, whose light shone far out to sea, and by the Great Square where the white tree Galathilion grew. It was ruled first by Ingwë and later by Finwë, and it became the greatest Elvish city of Aman, a symbol of Eldarin craft and memory.The Lonely Island off the coast of Valinor in the Bay of Eldamar, surrounded by the Enchanted Isles, an arrowhead-shaped green land whose name reflects its original isolation in the midst of Belegaer. Ulmo moved it back and forth across the sea to ferry the Elves to Aman, and afterward it was anchored just off Aman's eastern shore. The island became the dwelling of the Teleri of Aman, and later a home for many Eldar who returned from Middle-earth at the end of the First Age. Its principal city is Avallónë on the eastern shore, and light from the Calacirya made its lands fertile and fair, with the West visible beyond the sea.Unintelligent humanoid creatures created by Morgoth before the First Age as servants and instruments of destruction. Made as mockeries of the Ents, though without the wisdom or nobility of Yavanna's shepherds, they served the Dark Lord's purposes in war and terror. Strong and brutal but slow of wit, they were vulnerable to sunlight which turned them to stone.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>A Vala, the most warlike of the Valar and the spouse of Nessa. Tulkas was so strong and quick that he needed neither weapon nor steed, and he delighted in deeds of prowess and strength such as wrestling and fighting. His flesh was ruddy, his hair and beard golden, and his laughter was loud in sport and war. He came to Arda after the other Valar had begun their struggle with Melkor, and his arrival helped bring about the Spring of Arda. A hardy friend, he was slow to wrath but also slow to forgive, quick in action, and not good in counsel.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Second son of Fingolfin, younger brother of Fingon and elder brother of Aredhel and Argon. In Aman he married Elenwë of the Vanyar, and they had a daughter, Idril Celebrindal. Guided by visions from Ulmo, he discovered the hidden valley of Tumladen and there founded Gondolin, the Hidden City, building it in secret over many years. The city was concealed by the Encircling Mountains and guarded by the Eagles of Thorondor, making Turgon one of the great hidden rulers of the Noldor.The first great lights of Arda in the Spring of Arda: Illuin in the far north and Ormal in the far south. They were wrought by Aulë at Yavanna's request so that her planted seeds could grow, filled with light by Varda, and hallowed by Manwë. Each lamp was set on a mighty pillar taller than any later mountains, with Illuin shining a blue light from Helcar in the north and Ormal shining a golden light from Ringil in the south. Where their lights mingled, the Great Lake and the island Almaren lay, and there the Valar first dwelt; the world was lit as if in a changeless day. Melkor later cast down the pillars and broke the Lamps, shattering the symmetry of Arda, forming new seas, and driving the Valar to retreat to Aman, where they later made the Two Trees.The sacred trees Telperion and Laurelin that brought light to Valinor during the Years of the Trees, after the destruction of the Two Lamps and before the rising of the Sun and Moon. Sung into being by Yavanna on the green mound of Ezellohar outside Valimar, they grew in the presence of all the Valar and were watered by the tears of Nienna. Telperion the elder was silver with dark green leaves shining silver beneath, and Laurelin the younger was golden with gold-edged leaves, and each waxed and waned in turn so that Valinor was never without light. Their mingled radiance upon Aman was holy and beautiful beyond measure, and the true light of the Trees before their poisoning was said to reside only in the Silmarils of Fëanor. In the Darkening of Valinor, Melkor and Ungoliant destroyed both Trees, draining their light and leaving them withered. From their last flower and fruit the Valar made the Moon and Sun, and descendants of Telperion survived as the White Trees of Númenor and Gondor. The destruction of the Two Trees marked the end of an age and the beginning of the First Age of the Children of Ilúvatar.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>Lady of the Seas, a Maia of Ulmo and spouse of Ossë. She loved and protected all creatures and weeds that live in the sea, brought calm seas, and could calm the tumultuous waves of her husband; for this she was loved by mariners. It was said that her hair spread through all the surface of water. Early in the history of Arda, after Ossë was corrupted by Morgoth, Aulë pleaded with Uinen to persuade him to return to the service of Ulmo.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>Lord of Waters, King of the Sea, and Dweller of the Deep, one of the Aratar and third in majesty after Manwë and Varda. All waters are under his government, from the great ocean Ekkaia to bays and rivers and even the waters under the earth. His spirit runs in the very veins of the world, and he dwells not in Valinor but in the deeps of the seas around and below Ambar. Of all the Ainur he was most deeply instructed in music; he speaks through the sound of water and makes music through his great horns, the Ulumúri. When he appears, he is dreadful and terrible as a mounting wave that strides to the land, clad in shimmering silver-green mail and wearing a dark foam-crested helm, with a voice deep like the ocean. He cared for Arda and the Children of Eru, and alone of the Valar never forsook them.Melkor's first and greatest fortress, built after his arrival in Arda beneath the Iron Mountains where the light of the Two Lamps was dim and cold. From this stronghold the blight of his hatred spread and the Spring of Arda was marred. It was delved exceedingly deep, with pits of fire, caverns, and vaults hidden with deceit, and it housed great hosts of servants; the far north became desolate under its shadow. It served as Melkor's base until the Valar assailed it, broke its gates, and unroofed it, taking Melkor captive to Valinor. Angband began as a lesser fortress to the west of Utumno and later became its successor.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>The Weaver, one of the Valier and the wife of Mandos. She is responsible for weaving the story of the World, with which the Halls of Mandos are clothed and ever widen. Her work gives her a quiet but profound place among the Powers, preserving the memory of Arda in woven form. Her Quenya name means Weaver or Ever-weaving, derived from the root WIR; in The Etymologies it is connected with a root meaning wind or weave.The Powers of the World, the mightiest of the Ainur who entered Arda to complete its material development after the Music of the Ainur determined its form. Fourteen great spirits took up this responsibility, becoming the shapers and rulers of the world, each with particular dominion over aspects of creation. Dwelling in the Blessed Realm of Valinor in the Uttermost West, they guided the destiny of Arda and summoned the Elves to dwell with them in the light of the Two Trees.The City of Many Bells at the heart of Valinor, where many of the Valar and Maiar dwelt. It lay near Ezellohar, the green mound where the Two Trees grew, on the Girdle of Arda in the east-central Plains of Valinor, west of Taniquetil. The city is described as a place of splendor, with houses roofed in gold, floors of silver, and doors of polished bronze, their stones lifted with spells and bound with magic. Its name means the dwelling of the Valar, emphasizing its role as the central habitation of the Powers in the Blessed Realm.The realm of the Valar in central Aman, established after Almaren was destroyed and properly referring to the inhabited lands of the continent. It was home to the Valar and to the Vanyar, Noldor, and some of the Teleri, with Valimar as its central city and Tol Eressëa lying just off its eastern shore. The Pelóri were raised to the east as a defense against Melkor, while Ekkaia lay to the west, and the land was hallowed and stainless, free from sickness or decay. The Two Trees grew on Ezellohar and lit the realm, and the great Elvish cities of Tirion and Alqualondë were built there.The Fair Elves, the first and smallest of the three kindreds of the Eldar, descending from all the Minyar who accepted the summons to Valinor. All among them possessed golden hair, and they were the most beloved of Manwë and Varda, dwelling upon Taniquetil and in the plains of Valinor. Led by Ingwë, they were first to arrive in the Blessed Realm and never departed from it save when they marched to war against Morgoth in the final battle of the First Age.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>Queen of the Valar and Lady of the Stars, one of the Aratar. Wife of Manwë and mightiest of the Valier, dwelling with him upon Taniquetil. Called Elbereth Gilthoniel by the Elves in Sindarin, and Elentári, Star-Queen, in Quenya. Too great is her beauty to be declared in words of Men or Elves, for the light of Ilúvatar lives still in her face, and in light is her power and her joy. Knows all the regions of Eä and rejoices in light. Filled the Two Lamps with radiance during the Spring of Arda. Before the awakening of the Elves, she undertook her greatest work: taking the dew from the vats of Telperion, she created new and brighter stars, setting many individual stars and also constellations, including Carnil, Luinil, Nénar, Lumbar, Alcarinquë, Elemmírë, and the Sickle of the Valar. Together with Manwë she sees beyond all eyes through mist and darkness, and with him hears all voices from every corner of the world. In Middle-earth she is most revered by the Elves, who call upon her name and sing hymns to her. The very mention of her name is said to be deadly to evil spirits. Her name Varda means "Sublime," "Exalted," or "Lofty" in Quenya.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Voronwë Aranwion, called the Steadfast, was a mariner of Gondolin and son of Aranwë, a nobleman related to the House of Fingolfin. His mother was one of the Sindar of the Falas, descended from the people of Círdan, giving him both Noldorin and Sindarin heritage. Connected with the will of Ulmo, he became a guide to Tuor through the wastes and perils of Beleriand toward the hidden entrance of Gondolin.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>The Ever-young, one of the Valier. Younger sister of Yavanna and spouse of Oromë. Possesses influence over the flora and fauna of Middle-earth. All flowers spring as she passes and open if she glances upon them, and all birds sing at her coming. Dwells in gardens filled with golden flowers, and often comes to the forests of Oromë. The Maia Arien tended the golden flowers of her gardens, watering them with the bright dews from Laurelin in the days of the Two Trees. Melian also served Vána and Estë before departing to Middle-earth. Her name means "beautiful" in Quenya, related to unmarred beauty.The final and greatest conflict of the Wars of Beleriand, fought between the Host of the West sent by the Valar and the forces of Morgoth, lasting more than four decades from the years 545 to 587 of the First Age. Eärendil the Mariner came before the Valar bearing a Silmaril upon his brow and delivered the errand of the Two Kindreds, begging for pardon for the Noldor and for aid against Morgoth's tyranny, and the Valar were moved by his plea and resolved at last to intervene. The Host of the West was gathered in Aman, including the Vanyar who had never come to Middle-earth, the Noldor of Valinor, many of the Maiar, and the host sailed east in the ships of the Falmari while Eärendil rose into the heavens as a living star. When the Host landed in Middle-earth the war was joined, and the struggle was long and devastating, with the shape of the world broken and remade by the fury of the battles. In the final years Morgoth unleashed his last weapon, the winged dragons led by Ancalagon the Black, the mightiest of all dragons, and they drove back the Host of Valinor until Eärendil came in his sky-ship Vingilótë with Thorondor and the great Eagles, and they fought the dragons through the air. After a day-long battle Eärendil slew Ancalagon, and the dragon fell upon Thangorodrim and broke its towers in his ruin. Morgoth fled to the deepest pits of Angband but was dragged forth, and when he sued for pardon his feet were hewn from under him and he was cast down. The Valar bound him with the chain Angainor, took from him the two remaining Silmarils, and thrust him through the Door of Night beyond the Walls of the World into the Timeless Void, never to return until the End of Days. The devastation of the War was so great that most of Beleriand sank beneath the waves of Belegaer, and only Lindon endured in the west. The War of Wrath ended the Elder Days and the long First Age, and the few faithful Edain who survived were given Númenor as their reward, while the exiled Noldor were pardoned and many returned to Valinor.A race of evil wolves known by the Northmen of Rhovanion as Wargs or Wild Wolves. They were an evil breed, possibly inhabited by evil spirits, though their origin is uncertain. Wargs were seen in Rhovanion and were often allied with Orcs of the Misty Mountains, who used them as mounts. They were clever, spoke a dreadful language of their own, feared fire, and could not climb trees.The southernmost summit of the Weather Hills, known in Sindarin as Amon Sûl, the Hill of the Wind. It stood somewhat apart from the other hills and had a flattened conical top. In older days it marked the boundary between Arthedain and Rhudaur, near the East Road in the central lands of Arnor. A tower had stood there since the days of Elendil, and within it was kept a palantír. The hill therefore became a coveted and strategic place in the divided North-kingdom, later remembered as a ruined but important landmark in Eriador.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>The Giver of Fruits and Queen of the Earth, one of the Aratar. Called Kementári, meaning Queen of the Earth. Elder sister of Vána and spouse of Aulë, with whom she dwells in central Valinor. Lover of all things that grow in the earth, holding countless forms in her mind, from the trees like towers in forests long ago to the moss upon stones and the small secret things in the mould. All growing things answer to her, both the olvar that are rooted in place and the kelvar that move freely. In reverence she is next to Varda among the Queens of the Valar. Her usual form is that of a tall woman robed in green, though at times she takes other shapes. Some have seen her standing like a tree under heaven, crowned with the Sun and with roots plunging into the waters beneath. From her thoughts came the shapes of the Two Trees of Valinor, Telperion and Laurelin. At her request, Eru gave life to the Ents as shepherds of the trees. Her name means "Giver of Fruits" in Quenya.A Khuzdul word appearing as a short form of Zirakzigil, the Dwarves' name for the mountain called Celebdil or Silvertine. It belongs to the Dwarvish naming of the three Mountains of Moria, which Gimli referred to as Baraz, Zirak, and Shathûr. Since zigil appears to mean silver, Zirak is understood as tine, preserving the mountain's identity as the silver spike or Silvertine above Khazad-dûm.<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Third child and second daughter of Finwë and his second wife Indis of the Vanyar. Sister to Findis, Fingolfin, and Finarfin, and half-sister to Fëanor. Known more commonly by her mother-name Lalwendë, or in shortened form Lalwen, she was particularly close to her brother Fingolfin. Her name Írimë is Quenya, likely a feminine form of írima, meaning desirable or lovely, and her story belongs to Tolkien's later accounts of the House of Finwë.Those not of Aman, the term the Noldorin Exiles used to describe those Eldar who set out on the Great Journey but remained in Middle-earth without completing it. This geographic designation particularly applied to the Sindar, but could encompass the Laiquendi and more broadly all the Nandor. The term arose as a more polite alternative to Moriquendi when the returning Noldor found that the Sindar were offended by being classified among the Elves of Darkness, despite their Grey-elven nobility and the greatness of their kingdoms.